第二版及修订版前言编者注

PREFACE to the Second and Revised Edition By the Editor

如果我那位可怜的“平面国”朋友，在开始撰写这些回忆录时，依然保持着他那股活力，现在我就无需在这篇序言中为他代笔了。他想在序言中，首先向“空间国”的读者和评论家们致谢，他们的赞赏以出乎意料的迅捷，促使他的作品得以再版；其次，为某些错误和印刷错误致歉（但这并非他本人的全部责任）；第三，解释一两个误解。但他已今非昔比。多年的牢狱之灾，以及更加沉重的普遍怀疑和嘲笑，加上年事已高，抹去了他在“空间国”短暂停留期间积累的许多思想、观念，甚至许多术语。因此，他请求我代表他回应两点特别的反对意见，一个是知识层面的，另一个是道德层面的。

If my poor Flatland friend retained the vigour of mind which he enjoyed when he began to compose these Memoirs, I should not now need to represent him in this Preface, in which he desires, firstly, to return his thanks to his readers and critics in Spaceland, whose appreciation has, with unexpected celerity, required a second edition of his work; secondly, to apologize for certain errors and misprints (for which, however, he is not entirely responsible); and, thirdly, to explain one or two misconceptions. But he is not the Square he once was. Years of imprisonment, and the still heavier burden of general incredulity and mockery, have combined with the natural decay of old age to erase from his mind many of the thoughts and notions, and much also of the terminology, which he acquired during his short stay in Spaceland. He has, therefore, requested me to reply in his behalf to two special objections, one of an intellectual, the other of a moral nature.

第一个反对意见是，平面国人看到一条线时，看到的线在肉眼看来既粗又长（否则，如果它没有一定的厚度，就看不见了）；因此，有人认为，他应该承认他的同胞不仅又长又宽，而且（尽管程度无疑很小）也厚又高。这种反对意见很有道理，而且对于太空国人来说，几乎无法抗拒。因此，我承认，当我第一次听到这个反对意见时，我一时不知该如何回答。但我可怜的老朋友的回答在我看来完全符合我的要求。

The first objection is, that a Flatlander, seeing a Line, sees something that must be thick to the eye as well as long to the eye (otherwise it would not be visible, if it had not some thickness); and consequently he ought (it is argued) to acknowledge that his countrymen are not only long and broad, but also (though doubtless to a very slight degree) thick or high. This objection is plausible, and, to Spacelanders, almost irresistible, so that, I confess, when I first heard it, I knew not what to reply. But my poor old friend’s answer appears to me completely to meet it.

“我承认，”当我向他提出这个反对意见时，他说，“我承认你批评者提出的事实是真实的，但我否认他的结论。在平面国里，我们确实有一个未被认识的第三维度，叫做‘高度’，就像你在太空国度，确实存在着一个未被认识的第四维度，目前尚无定论，但我称之为“额外高度”。但我们无法感知到我们的“高度”，正如你们无法感知到你们的“额外高度”一样。即使是我——我曾经去过太空国度，并且有幸在二十四小时内理解了“高度”的含义——现在也无法理解它，也无法通过视觉或任何理性过程来体会它：我只能通过信仰来领悟它。

“I admit,” said he—when I mentioned to him this objection—“I admit the truth of your critic’s facts, but I deny his conclusions. It is true that we have really in Flatland a Third unrecognized Dimension called ‘height’, just as it is also true that you have really in Spaceland a Fourth unrecognized Dimension, called by no name at present, but which I will call ‘extra-height.’ But we can no more take cognizance of our ‘height’ than you can of your ‘extra-height.’ Even I—who have been in Spaceland, and have had the privilege of understanding for twenty-four hours the meaning of ‘height’—even I cannot now comprehend it, nor realise it by the sense of sight or by any process of reason: I can but apprehend it by faith.

原因显而易见。维度意味着方向，意味着测量，意味着多与少。现在，我们所有的线都是同样且无限粗细（或者说无限高，随便你怎么称呼）；因此，它们中没有任何东西可以引导我们的思维去理解那个维度。任何“精密的千分尺”——正如一位过于草率的太空国批评家所建议的那样——都对我们毫无用处；因为我们不知道该测量什么，也不知道测量的方向。当我们看到一条线时，我们看到的是又长又亮的东西；亮度和长度对于线的存在都是必要的；如果亮度消失，线就消失了。因此，当我和所有平面国的朋友谈论那种以某种方式在一条线上可见的未被认识的维度时，他们会说：“啊，你指的是亮度”；而当我回答“不，我指的是一个真正的维度”时，他们立刻反驳道：“那就测量它，或者告诉我们它延伸的方向。”让我沉默，因为我什么也做不了。就在昨天，首席圆桌（换句话说，我们的大祭司）来视察州立监狱，对我进行了他第七次年度视察，他第七次问我：“我进步了吗？”我试图向他证明他既“高”，又“长”又“宽”，尽管他自己并不知道。但他怎么回答的？“你说我‘高’；衡量一下我的‘高’，我就相信你。”我能做什么？我该如何应对他的挑战？我被击垮了；他得意洋洋地离开了房间。

“The reason is obvious. Dimension implies direction, implies measurement, implies the more and the less. Now, all our lines are equally and infinitestimally thick (or high, whichever you like); consequently, there is nothing in them to lead our minds to the conception of that Dimension. No ‘delicate micrometer’—as has been suggested by one too hasty Spaceland critic—would in the least avail us; for we should not know what to measure, nor in what direction. When we see a Line, we see something that is long and bright; brightness, as well as length, is necessary to the existence of a Line; if the brightness vanishes, the Line is extinguished. Hence, all my Flatland friends—when I talk to them about the unrecognized Dimension which is somehow visible in a Line—say, ‘Ah, you mean brightness’: and when I reply, ‘No, I mean a real Dimension,’ they at once retort, ‘Then measure it, or tell us in what direction it extends’: and this silences me, for I can do neither. Only yesterday, when the Chief Circle (in other words our High Priest) came to inspect the State Prison and paid me his seventh annual visit, and when for the seventh time he put me the question, ‘Was I any better?’ I tried to prove to him that he was ‘high,’ as well as long and broad, although he did not know it. But what was his reply? ‘You say I am “high”; measure my “high-ness” and I will believe you.’ What could I do? How could I meet his challenge? I was crushed; and he left the room triumphant.

这对你来说还觉得奇怪吗？那就换个角度想想吧。假设一位四维空间的人屈尊来拜访你，说：“每当你睁开眼睛，你都会看到一个平面（二维），并由此推断出一个立体（三维）；但实际上，你也看到了（尽管你没有意识到）一个四维空间，它既不是颜色，也不是亮度，也不是任何类似的东西，而是一个真正的维度，尽管我无法指出它的方向，你也无法测量它！”你会对这样的访客说什么？你不会把他关起来吗？好吧，这就是我的命运：我们平面国的人因为宣扬三维空间而把一个正方形关起来，就像你们太空国的人因为宣扬四维空间而把一个立方体关起来一样自然。唉，在所有维度中，盲目而又迫害人类的家族相似性是多么强烈啊！点、线、正方形、立方体、超立方体——我们都容易犯同样的错误，都同样是我们各自维度偏见的奴隶，正如我们的一位空间国诗人所说——

“Does this still seem strange to you? Then put yourself in a similar position. Suppose a person of the Fourth Dimension, condescending to visit you, were to say, ‘Whenever you open your eyes, you see a Plane (which is of Two Dimensions) and you infer a Solid (which is of Three); but in reality you also see (though you do not recognize) a Fourth Dimension, which is not colour nor brightness nor anything of the kind, but a true Dimension, although I cannot point out to you its direction, nor can you possibly measure it! What would you say to such a visitor? Would not you have him locked up? Well, that is my fate: and it is as natural for us Flatlanders to lock up a Square for preaching the Third Dimension, as it is for you Spacelanders to lock up a Cube for preaching the Fourth. Alas, how strong a family likeness runs through blind and persecuting humanity in all Dimensions! Points, Lines, Squares, Cubes, Extra-Cubes—we are all liable to the same errors, all alike the Slaves of our respective Dimensional prejudices, as one of our Spaceland poets has said—

“大自然的一点触动，让所有世界变得相似。”” *

‘One touch of Nature makes all worlds akin.’ ”*

在这一点上，我认为正方形的辩护是无懈可击的。我希望我能说，他对第二个（或道德）反对意见的回答同样清晰有力。有人反对他厌恶女性，而由于这一反对意见受到了那些被造物主构成了空间国种族中较大一半的人的强烈支持，我愿意在力所能及的范围内删除它。但是正方形对空间国的道德术语的使用如此不习惯，如果我逐字逐句地抄录他对这一指控的辩护，那对他来说就太不公平了。因此，作为他的解读者和总结者，我了解到，在七年的监禁期间，他自己也改变了自己对女性以及等腰三角形或下等三角形的看法。就他个人而言，他现在倾向于球体的观点，即直线在许多重要方面都优于圆形。但是，作为一名历史学家，他把自己与平面国乃至太空国历史学家普遍采用的观点（或许过于接近）联系起来；在这些历史学家的著作中（直到最近），女性和人类大众的命运很少被认为值得一提，也从未被认真考虑过。

On this point the defense of the Square seems to me to be impregnable. I wish I could say that his answer to the second (or moral) objection was equally clear and cogent. It has been objected that he is a woman-hater, and as this objection has been vehemently urged by those whom Nature’s decree has constituted the somewhat larger half of the Spaceland race, I should like to remove it, so far as I can honestly do so. But the Square is so unaccustomed to the use of the moral terminology of Spaceland that I should be doing him an injustice if I were literally to transcribe his defense against this charge. Acting, therefore, as his interpreter and summarizer, I gather that in the course of an imprisonment of seven years he has himself modified his own personal views, both as regards Women and as regards the Isosceles or Lower Classes. Personally, he now inclines to the opinion of the Sphere that the Straight Lines are in many important respects superior to the Circles. But, writing as a Historian, he has identified himself (perhaps too closely) with the views generally adopted by Flatland, and (as he has been informed) even by Spaceland, Historians; in whose pages (until very recent times) the destinies of Women and of the masses of mankind have seldom been deemed worthy of mention and never of careful consideration.

在一段更加晦涩难懂的文字中，他现在想要否认一些批评家理所当然地认为他具有的“圆形”或贵族倾向。他一方面公正地评价了少数“圆形”凭借其智慧，世世代代以来一直统治着无数同胞，另一方面又认为，平面国的种种事实，无需他多言，便足以说明：革命并非总是可以通过屠杀来压制，而大自然判处“圆形”不孕不育，也注定了它们最终的失败——“而在此，”他说道，“我看到了所有世界的伟大法则的应验：当人类的智慧认为自己在做一件事时，自然的智慧却迫使它去做另一件事，一件截然不同、更美好的事。”至于其他方面，他恳请读者不要以为……平面国的日常生活必然与空间国的一些其他细节相对应；然而，他希望，从整体上看，他的作品能够给那些心地温和谦逊的空间国人带来启发和乐趣，这些人在谈论那些极其重要但又超越经验的事情时，一方面拒绝说“这绝不可能”，另一方面拒绝说“事情必然如此，我们对此了如指掌”。

In a still more obscure passage he now desires to disavow the Circular or aristocratic tendencies with which some critics have naturally credited him. While doing justice to the intellectual power with which a few Circles have for many generations maintained their supremacy over immense multitudes of their countrymen, he believes that the facts of Flatland, speaking for themselves without comment on his part, declare that Revolutions cannot always be suppressed by slaughter, and that Nature, in sentencing the Circles to infecundity, has condemned them to ultimate failure—“and herein” he says, “I see a fulfilment of the great Law of all worlds, that while the wisdom of Man thinks it is working one thing, the wisdom of Nature constrains it to work another, and quite a different and far better, thing.” For the rest, he begs his readers not to suppose that every minute detail in the daily life of Flatland must needs correspond to some other detail in Spaceland; and yet he hopes that, taken as a whole, his work may prove suggestive, as well as amusing, to those Spacelanders of moderate and modest minds who—speaking of that which is of the highest importance, but lies beyond experience—decline to say on the one hand, “This can never be,” and on the other hand, “It must needs be precisely thus, and we know all about it.”

*作者希望我补充一点，他的一些批评者对此事的误解促使他在与球体的对话中插入了一些与问题有关的评论，而这些评论之前被他忽略了，因为它们既乏味又不必要。

* The Author desires me to add, that the misconception of some of his critics on this matter has induced him to insert in his dialogue with the Sphere, certain remarks which have a bearing on the point in question, and which he had previously omitted as being tedious and unnecessary.

平面国：简介

FLATLAND: AN INTRODUCTION

托马斯·F·班乔夫

Thomas F. Banchoff

《平面国》首次出现于一百多年前，自那时起已出版了十几个不同的版本。为什么现在在普林斯顿科学图书馆发行这本书的新版本？对于每一代读者来说，埃德温·阿伯特·阿伯特关于不同维度生物相遇的经典故事都有着不同的意义。1884 年，对维多利亚时代英国有限视角的社会讽刺与对使用类比处理高维度的评论同样重要，而这两个要素都在第二版的引言中得到了澄清，据称是由一位编辑撰写，但实际上是阿伯特本人撰写的。当这本书于 1926 年重新发行时，考虑高维度的主要刺激因素是相对论，阿伯特的物理学家学生威廉·加内特撰写了新的引言。 1952年，该书首次出版现代版时，物理学家巴内什·霍夫曼（Banesh Hoffmann）再次撰写了序言，其中提到了维度类比与空间曲率之间的联系。近期，其他一些序言的作者包括科幻和奇幻作家、计算机科学家以及社会历史学家。

Flatland first appeared over one hundred years ago and a dozen different editions have been published since then. Why now put out a new edition of this book in the Princeton Science Library? For each generation of readers, Edwin Abbott Abbott’s classic story of encounter between beings from different dimensions has had different significance. In 1884, the social satire of the limited perspective of Victorian England was as important as the comments on the use of analogy in treating higher dimensions, and both of these elements were clarified by the introduction to the second edition, purportedly written by an editor but actually written by Abbott himself. When the book was reissued in 1926, the main stimulus for considering higher dimensions was relativity theory, and a new introduction was written by William Garnett, a physicist student of Abbott’s. In 1952, when the first modern edition appeared, it was again a physicist, Banesh Hoffmann, who wrote the introduction, referring to the connetion between the dimensional analogy and the curvature of space. Other recent introductions have come from science-fiction and fantasy writers, a computer scientist, and a social historian.

在我们这个时代，我们有新的理由重新审视这本书及其基本思想。阿博特挑战他的读者，想象一下，如果他们直接看到的只是低维切片，他们试图理解高维现象的本质会是什么样子。这正是当今放射科医生在分析CAT扫描或磁共振成像生成的切片时所面临的情况，他们试图通过研究物体的平面横截面来重建物体在空间中的形态。但阿博特并没有这样做。希望读者止步于对三维空间的二维表达：如果我们将同样的技术应用到更高的一维空间，并尝试通过考虑三维横截面来构想空间四维中的物体，会发生什么？对于阿伯特时代的数学家来说，这一挑战令人望而生畏。他们的方法足以可视化三维空间中的表面，但要将这些技术应用于更高维度的物体却困难重重。研究人员往往越来越依赖形式化和抽象化的方法，而忽略了图像。

In our own day, there are new reasons to reconsider this book and its fundamental ideas. Abbott challenged his readers to imagine trying to understand the nature of phenomena in higher dimensions if all they could see directly were lower-dimensional slices. That is precisely the situation that radiologists face today as they analyze the slices produced by CAT scans or magnetic resonance imaging, in attempts to reconstruct the forms of objects in space by studying their planar cross-sections. But Abbott did not want his readers to stop at two-dimensional representations of the third dimension: What would happen if we were to apply the same techniques one dimension higher, and attempt to conceive objects from a spatial fourth dimension by considering three-dimensional cross-sections? For mathematicians in Abbott’s day, that challenge was daunting. Their methods were adequate for visualizing surfaces in three-dimensional space, but it was only with great difficulty that these techniques could be applied to objects from higher dimensions. Frequently, researchers relied more and more on formal and abstract methods, leaving images behind.

然而，如今人们对可视化又燃起了新的兴趣，这主要是因为现代计算机图形学的出现，它能够将这些更高维度的事物真实地展现在人们的视野中。我们可以在四维空间中操控物体，并在计算机屏幕上看到它们的三维切片翻滚。但是，我们该如何解读这些图像呢？没有比《平面国》（Flatland）这本书更能解答如何处理高维切片现象的难题了。

Now, however there is a new interest in visualization, primarily because of the emergence of modern computer graphics, which can literally bring these higher dimensions into view. We can manipulate objects in four dimensions and see their three-dimensional slices tumbling on the computer screen. But how do we interpret these images? There is no better introduction to the problem of dealing with higher-dimensional slicing phenomena than this book, Flatland.

欣赏《平面国》并非必须读导言，读者不妨先读完这本书，稍后再回头看看导言是否能解答读者的一些疑问。在这篇简短的评论中，我们将探讨《平面国》中的讽刺元素，概述艾伯特的背景和兴趣，概述该作品的风格和历史背景，并探讨《平面国》对当代高维可视化新模式（尤其是计算机图形学）的影响。

It is not necessary to read an introduction to appreciate Flatland, and at this point the reader might be encouraged to go ahead and read the book, returning to the introduction only later on to see if some of the questions that arise are answered here. In this short commentary, we shall address the satirical elements in Flatland, sketch Abbott’s background and interests, provide overviews of the style and historical context of the work, and investigate Flatland’s influence on contemporary approaches to new modes of visualization of higher dimensions, particularly computer graphics.

《平面国》中的社会讽刺

Social Satire in Flatland

一百多年前，埃德温·阿博特·阿博特写下这部小巨作，出于多种原因。其中一些原因对他的读者来说显而易见，至今依然清晰可见。其他一些原因，阿博特本人则在第二版的导言中进行了解释，该书在第一版出版一个月后，即1884年底出版。还有一些原因，维多利亚时代的读者一眼就能看懂，但对于我们今天的读者来说，则需要一些澄清。幸运的是，这位杰出作家的四十五本书和其他著作中，提供了足够的直接和间接证据，可以解答许多问题，尽管并非全部，因为这个主题本身仍在不断激励我们提出新的问题。

When Edwin Abbott Abbott wrote his little masterpiece over one hundred years ago, he did it for several reasons. Some of these were obvious to his readers and remain obvious today. Others had to be explained by Abbott himself in the introduction to the second edition, which followed one month after the first, at the end of 1884. Still others were immediately clear to Victorian readers but need some clarification for readers in our day. Fortunately, there is enough evidence, direct and indirect, in this remarkable author’s forty-five books and other writings to give us answers to many questions, though not all, since the subject itself continues to encourage us to raise new ones.

首先要讨论的问题是《平面国》中对女性的待遇。阿博特是一位社会改革家，他批判了维多利亚时代社会诸多方面的局限性。他坚信教育机会平等，不分社会阶层，尤其要尊重女性。他积极参与变革的努力，而他因教育机构的抵制而感到的挫败感，在《平面国》的讽刺作品中得到了体现。这是第一代女性被允许去牛津和剑桥上课，但她们的机会仍然相当有限。虽然有很多学校可以让男孩接受培训以应对要求严格的大学入学考试，但女孩却几乎没有类似的机会，许多考入大学的年轻女性，比如阿博特的女儿，大部分教育都是在家里接受的，通常是由私人教师指导。阿博特撰写了《家庭教育提示》的部分原因是为了帮助人们做到这一点，这本书面向希望帮助孩子为接受高等教育做准备的家长。阿博特也是教师培训联合会的积极领导者，该联合会由维多利亚时代英国的主要女性教育家组建并主要支持，她们广泛赞扬阿博特为教育改革所做的努力，特别是他提出了获得大学入学资格的替代方法。阻碍这些努力的狭隘态度在《平面国》中表现得非常清楚，在这本书中，女性被描绘成无法理解男性所受的教育。许多人忽视了女性生存的某个维度，正如《平面国》中将女性描绘成直线段所象征的那样。他们打着保护女性的旗号，阻止女性获得提升自身地位的途径。艾伯特在《平面国》的结尾清晰地表达了他对此事的看法，叙述者逐渐意识到，他的社会所压制的（女性）美德恰恰是最值得珍视的。

The first subject that has to be addressed is the treatment of women in Flatland. Abbott was a social reformer who criticized a great many aspects of the limitations of Victorian society. He was a firm believer in equality of educational opportunity, across social classes and in particular for women. He participated actively in the efforts to bring about changes, and the frustration he felt from the resistance of the educational establishment is mirrored in the satire of Flatland. This was the first generation in which women were permitted to attend classes at Oxford and Cambridge, but their access was still quite limited. Although there were many schools where a boy could be trained for the demanding university entrance examinations, there were few comparable opportunities for girls, and many of the young women who gained entrance to universities, like Abbott’s daughter, had received much of their education at home, often from private tutors. It was partially to aid in this effort that Abbott composed his Hints for Home Teaching, directed at parents who wished to help their children prepare for higher education. Abbott was also a vocal leader in the Teachers’ Training Syndicate, formed and primarily supported by the major female educators of Victorian England, who extensively praised Abbott for his efforts on behalf of education reform, in particular for proposing alternate ways of qualifying for entrance into university studies. The narrow-minded attitudes that blocked these efforts show up quite clearly in Flatland, where females are presented as incapable of comprehending the education given to males. Many people ignored one whole dimension of women’s existence, as symbolized by the representaiton of women in Flatland as straight line segments. Under the guise of protecting women, they kept them away from the means by which they might better their station. Abbott’s sentiments in this matter are clear by the end of Flatland, where the narrator comes to realize that the very (female) virtues his society has been putting down are ones that are to be most prized.

阿伯特是最早认识到“两种文化”社会含义的人之一。《平面国》中的男人是理性的缩影，强调了那些可以通过经验测量并用精确的科学语言描述的事物的重要性。那些无法量化的定性属性则被女性所掌控，因为她们不仅掌握着知识的直觉层面，还掌握着诸如忠诚和爱情等难以转化为严格功利主义概念的抽象概念。《平面国》的二维叙述者阿正方形自认为很有见地，他提出这样的观点：维持两种不同的语言——一种用于男人之间的对话，另一种用于与女人交谈——会对年轻人的思想造成太大的负担。男人的语言总是有可能被女人得知，这让人想起早期社会禁止教奴隶读书的禁令。

Abbott was one of the first to recognize the implications of a “two cultures” society. The men in Flatland epitomize the rational, emphasizing the importance of that which can be measured empirically and described in precise scientific language. Qualitative properties not susceptible to such quantification are relegated to the world of women, who have an absolute corner on not only the intuitve aspects of knowledge but also the abstract concepts such as loyalty and love which are difficult to translate into a strictly utilitarian construct. A Square, the two-dimensional narrator of Flatland, considers himself enlightened when he propounds the view that the strain of maintaining two separate languages, one for conversation among men and one for talking with women, exacts too great a toll on young minds. There is always the danger that the language of men will be revealed to women, reminiscent of the prohibitions in earlier societies against teaching slaves to read.

阿博特是一位拥有深厚传统道德感的宗教人士，他显然不认同盛行的科学主义知识观，并不止一次地指出让一个人的某一面完全支配另一面的危险。阿博特是一位推崇“平等”的教师，而《平面国》则将那种要么选择完全理性，要么选择完全直觉的单一倾向简化为荒谬。

As a religious man with a well-developed traditional sense of morality, Abbott clearly did not subscribe to the prevailing scientistic view of knowledge, and he more than once pointed out the dangers of letting one side of the personality completely dominate the other. Abbott was a teacher who extolled blanace, and Flatland reduces to an absurdity the single-minded tendency of choosing either the totally rationalistic or the totally intuitive.

《平面国》讽刺的另一个方面是对那些格格不入者的处理。在维多利亚时代英国僵化的社会中，对异常行为几乎毫无容忍度。异常行为常常与犯罪倾向联系在一起，一些理论将异常行为归咎于骨架或头骨的异常形状。异常者常常被隔离在精神病院，与社会其他成员隔离。社会其他成员对怪异的元素保持着浓厚的兴趣，精神病院通常设有观景台，以便普通人观察病人的活动和滑稽动作。阿博特建议以斯威夫特式的夸张手法消灭异常者，尤其考虑到他还制定了残酷的计划，将一些不幸的人作为实物教学对象，成为毫无权利的可消耗品，供《平面国》的普通学生学习。他对上流社会中出现异常现象的评论尤为尖锐。他的读者当然可以举出一些注定要获得高位却未能满足完成大学教育先决条件的人的例子。这样的人不适合从事低级工作，所以他们只会在社会上制造麻烦。艾伯特的解决方案堪比乔纳森·斯威夫特的《温和建议》：任何未通过大学期末考试的人都将被终身监禁或处以无痛苦的死刑。任何读者都应该明白这段话的讽刺意味。

Another aspect of the satire in Flatland is the treatment of those who did not fit in. In the rigid society of Victorian England, there was little tolerance for irregularity. It was often associated with criminal tendency, and some theories blamed deviant behavior on an abnormal shape in the frame or the scull. Frequently, the unusual were segregated from the rest of society in asylums. The rest of society maintained a fascination with the freakish element, and asylums often had viewing galleries so ordinary people could observe the activities and antics of the inmates. Abbott’s suggestion that irregulars be eliminated in a Swiftian exaggeration, especially when coupled with the cruel plan of keeping a number of these unfortunates available as object lessons, an expendable supply of individuals with no rights at all, to be studied by the regular Flatland pupils. Especially pointed are his remarks about the appearance of irregularities among the upper classes. His readers could certainly supply their own examples of men destined for high station who had failed to fulfill the prerequisites for completing a university education. Such people are not fit for lower employment, and so they simply cause trouble within society. Abbott’s solution is worthy of Jonathan Swift’s Modest Proposal: anyone who fails the final examinations of the university will be incarcerated for life or subjected to a painless death. No reader should miss the satirical intent of such a paragraph.

阿博特明确地将教育视为学生超越其出生社会阶层的一种手段，他尤其谴责那些利用教育来延续阶级差别的人。所有学生都应该接受基础的通识教育，这样他们中的一些人可以继续接受高等教育，而其他人则可以从更开明的视角进入商界。阿博特在伦敦城市学校的学生除了学习理论学科外，还学习了实用的科学和艺术。在《平面国》写作七年后，在课程分为“现代”和古典两部分的危机期间，阿博特辞去了校长职务。在《平面国》中，阿博特呼应了这场危机，他讽刺性地对比了下层阶级的“感觉”和社会中受过教育的那部分人更精致的“看法”。通过偏好更为疏离的感知方式，上层阶级在自己和下层阶级之间筑起了一道屏障。

Abbott definitely saw education as a means for students to transcend the social class into which they were born, and he was particularly censorious of the efforts of those who used education to perpetuate class distinctions. A basic liberal education should be provided to all students, so that some of them might go on to higher education and others might go into business from a more enlightened perspective. Abbott’s students at the City of London School learned practical science and art as well as theoretical subjects. Abbott resigned from the headmastership just seven years after the writing of Flatland, during a crisis over the splitting of the curriculum into seperate “modern” and classical sides. In Flatland, Abbott echoes this crisis as he satirically contrasts the “feeling” of the lower classes with the more refined “seeing” of the educated part of society. By preferring the more remote way of sensing, the higher classes built a barrier between themselves and the lower strata.

阿博特的几位学生打破了社会壁垒，非常乐意感谢他们的老老师。其中最著名的是英国首相阿斯奎斯勋爵，他出身卑微，却因在阿博特的指导下接受了古典教育而进入牛津大学。救世军第二任总干事布拉姆韦尔·布斯也感谢阿博特的鼓励和帮助他实现自我价值。以色列·戈兰茨爵士从伦敦城市学校毕业后，前往伦敦大学学习，当时犹太学生的受教育机会微薄。他总是把莎士比亚的著作寄给他的老老师，并劝说他加入英国学院——该学院是由戈兰茨参与创立的。显然，阿博特为他的前学生感到自豪，他更倾向于那种允许人们根据自身能力而非出生的社会阶层晋升的教育。他在《平面国》中讽刺的正是这种普遍存在的教育体系。

Several of Abbott’s students who broke societal barriers were only too happy to thank their old master. Most famous was the Prime Minister of England, H. H. Asquith, Lord Oxford, a man from humble background who gained entrance to Oxford as a result of his classical education under Abbott. Bramwell Booth, the second director general of the Salvation Army, also thanked Abbott for his encouragement and for promoting the development of his self-worth. Sir Israel Gollancz went on from the City of London School to study at the University of London at a time when educational opportunities for Jewish students were meager. He always sent his Shakespearean volumes to his old teacher, and induced him to accept membership into the British Academy, which Gollancz had helped to found. It is evident that Abbott was proud of his former pupils and that he preferred the kind of education that allowed people to rise on the basis of merit rather than of the societal class into which they were born. The prevailing system is the target of his satire in Flatland.

雅培的背景和兴趣

Abbott’s Background and Interests

《平面国》的作者是怎样的人？显然，阿博特对语言的力量印象深刻，而《平面国》则从多个层面探讨语言。全书或明或暗地都提及阿博特最喜爱的作家莎士比亚。读者不太可能辨认出其中的许多典故，因为维多利亚时代的人们虽然也观看过莎士比亚的戏剧，但他们并没有在学校里学习这些戏剧，除了伦敦城市学校。伦敦城市学校有以莎士比亚戏剧为基础的有奖考试传统，这促使聪明且竞争激烈的学生背诵大量戏剧内容，并将古典语言研究中常见的一些语言分析方法应用于伊丽莎白时代的英语。阿博特于1870年创作了他的第一部重要著作《莎士比亚语法》，并在他有生之年出版了数本新版，尽管直到世纪之交，他仍感叹，全英国的校长们甚至不愿将分配给拉丁语和希腊语的一小部分时间用于学习英语文学。阿博特本人写道，在准备莎士比亚著作的新版本时，他把所有剧本都重读了三遍。这也是一次精读。阿博特曾受其父埃德温·阿博特的培养。埃德温·阿博特是伦敦马里波恩语言学院的校长，也是蒲柏著作索引的编纂者，至今仍是该学科的主要参考书。阿博特协助父亲完成了这项工作，并为父亲的毕生著作撰写了序言。

What sort of person was the writer of Flatland? Clearly Abbott was impressed by the power of language, and Flatland is about language at several levels. Throughout the book there are overt and hidden references to Abbott’s favorite author, Shakespeare. It is unlikely that his readers would recognize many of the allusions, since although Victorians did attend Shakespearean plays, they did not study them in the schools, except at the City of London School. There a tradition of prize examinations based on Shakespeare led the bright and highly competitive students to memorize large portions of plays, and to apply to Elizabethan English some of the linguistic analysis that was common with scholarship in classical languages. Abbott wrote his first major book, A Shakespearean Grammar, in 1870, and several new editions appeared in his lifetime, even though he lamented as late as the turn of the century that headmasters throughout England were unwilling to turn over to the study of English literature even a small portion of the time allotted to Latin and Greek. Abbott himself writes that in preparing a new edition of his work on Shakespeare, he reread all of the plays for a third time. It was a close reading, too. Abbott had been trained by his father, Edwin Abbott, headmaster of the Philological School in Marylebone, London, and compiler of the concordance of the works of Pope that is still the major reference for that subject. Abbott aided his father in this enterprise and wrote the introduction to his father’s life’s work.

阿博特在思想上有些激进，他甚至建议以同样的力度运用古典学者发展的文学批评技巧来研究圣经。在为《大英百科全书》第九版撰写的有关福音书的颇具争议的文章中，阿博特建议用语言学测试来确定福音书和书信的年代和作者。他提到“曲线法”是一种分析风格和结构的方法，并哀叹这项工作对一个人来说太过繁重，这或许预示着我们如今可以通过计算机搜索定期进行阿博特梦寐以求的调查。这些建议对于那些希望将信仰建立在非科学基础之上的人来说自然是一种威胁。

Abbott was somewhat of an intellectual radical, going so far as to suggest that the techniques of literary criticism developed by classical scholars should be used with the same vigor to examine the Scriptures. In his controversial article on the Gospels for the ninth edition of the Encyclopaedia Britannica, Abbott suggests linguistics tests for the dating and the authorship of the Gospels and Epistles. He refers to the “method of curves” as a way of analyzing style and structure, and he laments that the work involved is too much for a single person, perhaps anticipating our present day when computer searches routinely carry out the kinds of investigation Abbott could only dream of. Such suggestions were naturally threatening to those who wished to base their faith on less scientific grounds.

教育体制僵化的部分原因在于考试占据着核心地位，考试首先决定着大学入学资格，其次决定着授予的学位。阿博特本人在这种体制下表现相当出色。从伦敦城市学校毕业时，他几乎在所有课程科目中都获奖。他曾就读于英语、法语、德语、拉丁语和希腊语，甚至还获得了数学奖。在剑桥大学，他获得了古典学第一名和校长奖章。同年，数学最高奖项被伦敦城市学校的另一位毕业生托马斯·斯特德曼·阿尔迪斯获得，他获得了第一名的“牧马人奖”（First Wrangler）和史密斯奖章。四项最高奖项全部颁给同一所学校的男生，这在当时并不常见，而且这所学校竟然是走读学校，而不是传统上在预科教育领域处于领先地位的英国公立学校，这更是闻所未闻。

Part of the rigidity of the educational system was due to the central place played by examinations, first for gaining entrance to the universities, and secondly for determining the sort of degree that would be awarded. Abbott himself did quite well under this system. By the time he had graduated from the City of London School, he had won prizes in just about all of the subjects in the curriculum. He had delivered prize declamations in English, French, German, Latin, and Greek, and he had even won a prize in mathematics. At Cambridge he was first in classics and Chancellor’s Medallist, the same year that the top mathematics prizes went to another graduate of the City of London School, Thomas Steadman Aldis, who was First Wrangler and Smith’s Prizeman. It was unusal for all four top prizes to go to boys from the same school, and unheard of that that school should be a day school, not one of the English public schools that were the traditional leaders in preparatory education.

平面国风格

The Style of Flatland

《平面国》的叙事风格与其他一些常见的异域游记略有不同，因为故事并非由访客讲述，而是由被访者讲述。这就像小人国的镇长讲述格列佛的故事，白兔讲述爱丽丝的冒险故事。直到书的后半部分，叙述者A方才得以讲述自己在更高维度生物造访后所引发的非凡事件中认知的转变。读者必须从头到尾读完故事，才能体会到叙述者身上发生的转变。同年出版的另一本书《哈克贝利·费恩历险记》的叙述者也经历了类似的转变。在书的开头，叙述者分享了他所在社会对奴隶制的偏见，而在沿河而下的旅程结束时，他的经历使他摒弃了这些观点。即便作者在书末表达的那些相对开明的观点，在当今时代也显得苍白无力，甚至可能未能准确体现作者的观点。然而，这部小说本身的价值在于它讲述了一个在陌生环境中感性发展的故事。《平面国》也展现了这一点。我们尚未消除这个世界上的种族偏见，也未平等对待女性，也未满足残疾人的需求。《平面国》中的社会教训仍在被汲取。

The narrative style of Flatland is somewhat different from some of the more familiar reports of visits to exotic lands, since the story is told not by the visitor but by the person visited. It is as if the story of Gulliver were told by the mayor of Lilliput or the advenutres of Alice by the White Rabbit. It is only in the latter half of the book that the narrator A Square can relate the changes that took place in his own perceptions as a result of the remarkable events caused by the visit of a being from a higher dimension. The reader has to stay with the story all the way through in order to appreciate the change that takes place in the storyteller. A similar thing happens with the narrator of another book written in exactly the same year, Huckleberry Finn. In the beginning of that book, the narrator shares the prejudices of his society with respect to slavery, and by the end of his journey down the river, his experiences have caused him to reject those views. Even the relatively enlightened ideas that the author expresses at the end of the book may seem inadequate in our present age, and they might not represent accurately the views of the author. Still, the novel itself is valuable for the tale it tells about the development of sensibility in a strange environment. That is what we have in Flatland as well. We have not erased racial prejudice from our world, nor do we treat women equally or provide for the needs of the handicapped. The social lessons of Flatland are still being learned.

《平面国》的历史背景

The Historical Context of Flatland

阿博特在《平面国》中的大部分作品都回应了他那个时代的数学和哲学关切，当时几何学家试图将四维及更高维度的现象可视化。他们画图、做模型，甚至尝试利用立体图像来观察四维物体的投影和切片。他们常常因无法同时看到多个不完整的图像而感到沮丧。随着计算机技术的出现，这一切都改变了。我们无法回答19世纪研究人员提出的所有问题，但我们可以用新的方式重新思考它们。阿伯特的二维叙述者带领读者完成了平面国公民在感知训练中都会进行的大部分练习，不断提升触觉和视觉，使其能够理解所有合理的形状。同样，在三维空间中，我们学习解读接收到的感知数据，逐渐达到能够解决歧义并从呈现给我们的视图中得出正确推论的程度。我们可以提升自身的建模和绘画能力，从而构建最有效的图像来准确地传达它们。随着概念变得越来越复杂，我们的局限性受到考验，最终我们会感到沮丧。当一个物体或结构无法在我们最信赖的信息接收方式——视觉平面上呈现时，尤其如此。这个问题可能与我们自身空间中事物的内在复杂性有关，也可能源于完全不同的原因，因为某些现象来自我们自身之外的空间，来自更高的维度。这与《平面国的正方形》所面临的问题类似。

Much of what Abbott wrote in Flatland came about in response to the mathematical and philosophical concerns of his day, when geometers attempted to visualize phenomena in the fourth and higher dimensions. They drew pictures and made models, and even attempted to use stereoscopic images in order to see what projections and slices of four-dimensional objects look like. They were often frustrated by their inability to see more than one incomplete image at a time. All that has changed with the advent of computer technology. We cannot answer all the questions raised by the investigators in the nineteenth century, but we can reconsider them in new ways. Abbott’s two-dimensional narrator led his readers through a good part of the exercises any citizen of Flatland would go through in the perception training, refining the sense of touch and sight so as to come to terms with all reasonable shapes. Similarly, we in three-space learn to interpret the sense data that come to us, gradually coming to the point where we can resolve ambiguities and draw correct inferences from the views presented to us. We can refine our own abilities to model and draw so as to construct the most effective images to communicate accurately about them. As the concepts become more and more complicated, our limitations become tested, and ultimately we experience frustration. This is especially true when an object or a configuration resists representation on the visual plane that is our most trusted means of receiving information. The problem may have to do with the intrinsic complexity of something in our own space, or it might be due to an entirely different reason, because some phenomenon comes from a space beyond our own, from a higher dimension. That is the analogue of the problem faced by A Square in Flatland.

阿博特并非第一个用不同维度的感知之谜来挑战读者的人。柏拉图早已运用了一个跨越维度界限的有力形象，他设想了一种人类，他们唯一的感官印象来自于洞穴壁上可见的阴影。如此有限的生物究竟能感知到多少三维的实体现实？当我们所能看到的只是上帝心中理想物体的实体阴影时，我们又能理解多少超越现实的真正本质？19世纪的德国和英国，几位作家开始构思想象二维空间中生物的体验。古斯塔夫·费希纳虚构了一个幻灯机投射在墙上的影子人的故事。卡尔·弗里德里希·高斯和赫尔曼·冯·亥姆霍兹都研究过一条在实体表面滑动的智慧扁形虫所能发现的几何形状。亥姆霍兹的思想在英国学术期刊中得到了广泛的体现，这些期刊探讨了高维空间的本质以及我们理解高维空间的能力。查尔斯·霍华德·辛顿在19世纪80年代初研究了二维平面生物的物理特性，阿博特很可能在创作《平面国》之前读过他的一篇或多篇文章。阿博特的挚友霍华德·坎德勒，也就是《平面国》的主人公，曾是阿宾厄姆学校的数学老师。欣顿在那里担任了几年的科学硕士。欣顿写道，他的目的是考察科学原理，而阿伯特的书的目的并非科学，而是“他的哲学和他的教训”。

Abbott was not the first person to challenge his readers with the enigmas of perceptions in different dimensions. Plato had already used a powerful image that crossed dimensional boundaries when he posited a race of men whose only sense impressions came from the shadows they could see on the wall of a cave. How little of the solid reality of the third dimension would such limited creatures be able to appreciate, and how little of the true nature of the transcendent reality do we comprehend when all we can see are the solid shadows of ideal objects in the mind of God. In the nineteenth century in Germany and England, several writers seized on the idea of imagining the experience of beings confined to two dimensions. Gustav Fechner made up the story of shadow man cast on a wall by a slide projector. Karl Friedrich Gauss and Hermann von Helmholz both investigated the kind of geometry that would be discovered by an intelligent flatworm sliding about on the surface of a solid object. Helmholz’s ideas were well represented in British intellectual journals, which ran debates about the nature of higher dimensions and our ability to comprehend them. Charles Howard Hinton examined the physical properties of the life of flat creatures on a two-dimensional surface in the early 1880s, and it is likely that Abbott could have seen one or more of his articles before he wrote Flatland. Abbott’s best friend, Howard Candler, the “H.C.” to whom Flatland is dedicated, was mathematics master at the Uppingham School, where Hinton spent several years as science master. Hinton wrote that his purpose was to examine scientific principles, while the purpose of Abbott’s book was not science but rather “his philosophy and his lessons.”

阿博特是首批意识到维度类比在探究不同维度生物之间联系方面所发挥的巨大作用的作家之一。在他后期的神学著作中，他进一步发展了这一思想，将其比作上帝无所不知的力量，上帝向冥冥之中的世界启示，并与那里的生物互动。阿博特也是首批利用切片概念通过研究平面横截面来获取固体信息的人之一。他熟悉通过记录圆形切片的面积来计算固体球体体积的过程，并且通过记录形状的不同横截面来探究欣赏形状的心理过程。对于一个正方形来说，从三维空间理解球体的性质是困难的，而理解甜甜圈的表面就更加困难了。

Abbott was one of the first writers to realize the full power of the dimensional analogy for investigating contact among beings from different dimensions. In his later theological works, he developed this idea further as an analogy for the all-seeing power of God, who makes revelations to a lower world and interacts with creatures there. Abbott was also one of the first to exploit the notion of slicing as a means of gaining information about solid objects by studying planar cross-sections. He was familiar with the process of calculating the volume of a solid ball by keeping track of the areas of circular slices, and he probed the psychological process of trying to appreciate a form by keeping track of its different cross-sections. It is difficult for A Square to comprehend the nature of a sphere from the third dimension. It would be even more difficult for him to comprehend the surface of a doughnut.

我们面临的挑战是显而易见的。正如一个球体穿过平面国，在《正方形》中它会被看作一个随时间增长然后收缩的圆圈一样，如果我们从一个四维空间访问一个超球面，我们可能会看到一个球体随时间增长然后收缩。将这种印象序列视为一个实体从更高维度逐渐显现的能力是任何想要接受《平面国》挑战的人的首要练习。更难的是书中暗示的关于三维和更高维度中正方形类似的练习。在文中，不同维度中立方体类似物的角数可以通过基于各种公式特征的论证来暗示。当这些立方体和超立方体以不同角度穿过切片平面或超平面时，想象它们会是什么样子并不容易。

The challenge for us is apparent. Just as a sphere penetrating Flatland is viewed by A Square as a circle growing and then shrinking in time, so also if we were visited by a hypersphere from a space of four dimensions, we might see a sphere growing and then shrinking in time. The ability to treat such a sequence of impressions as the gradual revelation of an entity from a higher dimension is the first exercise for anyone who wishes to accept the challenge of Flatland. More difficult is the exercise implied in the book concerning the analogue of a square in three and higher dimensions. In the text, the number of corners of analogues of cubes in different dimensions can be suggested by arguments based on the characteristics of various formulas. It is not so easy to imagine the ways in which such cubes and hypercubes appear when they are put through a slicing plane or hyperplane at different angles.

平面国和新的可视化模式

Flatland and New Modes of Visualization

如今，我们对“平面国”感兴趣的主要原因在于，我们首次能够实现祖先一个世纪前的梦想，获得对更高维度现象的直接视觉体验。实现这一目标的突破性进展是现代计算机图形学。在计算机屏幕上移动的图像可以让我们观察复杂的二维现象，例如网络和图案，也能让我们探究三维的复杂物体，例如建筑物或机器零件的平面图。当我们观看时，表盘的转动会使图像在屏幕上旋转，随着物体不同部分的呈现，揭示出结构的新方面和新的关系。

Today the major reason for our interest in Flatland is that for the first time we can achieve some of the dreams of our ancestors a century ago and obtain direct visual experience of phenomena in a dimension higher than our own. The breakthrough that brings this about is modern computer graphics. Images moving on a computer screen can give us a view of complicated two-dimensional phenomena like networks and patterns, and they can also enable us investigate complex objects in three dimensions, like the plans of a building or a machine part. As we watch, the turn of the dial makes the image spin around on the screen, revealing new aspects of the structure and new relationships as different parts of the object come into view.

建筑和机器部分都是三维的，每个点由三个坐标指定。每次取两个坐标，我们就能得到不同的立面图、正面图、侧面图和顶视图。计算机的计算速度足够快，可以从任何所需的角度显示混合视图。通过显示一系列视图（每秒三十个视图，每个视图都与前一个略有不同），计算机可以制作一部动画影片，比任何单张图片都能更好地展现三维物体的结构。

The building and the machine part are three-dimensional, with every point specified by three coordinates. Taking those coordinates two at a time gives us the different elevations, front, side, and top views. Computers can calculate quickly enough to display mixed views from any desired angle. By showing a sequence of views, thirty views every second, each slightly different from the previous one, the computer can create an animated film that reveals the structure of a three-dimensional object much better than any single picture.

如果说此类动画对于研究三维物体很有价值，那么它们对于我们理解四维或更高维度的现象则更为重要。建筑和机械设计领域的计算机技术帮助我们处理每个点由四个或更多坐标指定的集合。同样，我们一次显示两三个坐标，并运用想象力来理解整体关系，以便更有效地预测接下来会发生什么。

If such animations are valuable for studying three-dimensional objects, they are even more crucial in giving us insight into the phenomena in four or more dimensions. The computer techniques from architecture and machine design help us approach collections where each point is specified by four or more coordinates. Again, we show the coordinates two or three at a time, and use our imaginations to gain an appreciation of the overall relationships so we can more effectively predict what will come next.

这些技术威力的显著证据可以在放射学领域找到。CAT扫描和磁共振成像产生的数据集可以监测肿瘤在数周内的发展，所有信息都可以在计算机图形屏幕上进行分析。同样的技术也使地质学家能够研究数万年来全球变暖趋势的数据，或研究一个大型城市地区的经济状况，每个区域都能提供十几个不同类别的数值观测数据。计算机图形学在统计学中的应用极大地改变了这一学科，尤其是在探索性数据分析领域。

Dramatic evidence of the power of such techniques can be found in the field of radiology, where CAT scans and magnetic resonance imaging has produced data sets that can monitor the development of a tumor over the course of weeks, with all information available to be investigated on a computer graphics screen. Precisely the same kinds of techniques enable geologists to study the data on global warming trends over tens of thousands of years, or the economics of a large urban area, with each ward contributing numerical observations in a dozen different categories. The use of computer graphics in statistics has changed that subject in dramatic ways, especially in the area of exploratory data analysis.

时间与第四维

TIME AND THE FOURTH DIMENSION

“第四维度？那就是时间，不是吗？”不难想象A Square会如何反驳这个问题。他会把问题抛回给提问者，并提醒他，在《平面国》中，对引入第三维度概念的类似回应是：“第三维度？那就是时间，不是吗？”对于那些宇宙中存在第四维空间的生物来说，第五维就是分配给时间的维度，通常我们可以预期时间会紧随空间维度之后。一些现代物理学家认为，有十个维度的行为类似于空间，而第十一个维度是时间。问题在于，当我们将时间视为一个维度时，我们并不期望它的行为类似于空间中那些均匀可互换的维度。时空存在一套非常精细的数学，但这并非阿博特在《平面国》中指出的那种。在那里，我们被要求思考一个在各个方面都与前三个维度等同的第四维空间维度。事实上，为了介绍时空几何，几乎所有物理学家都会降低维度用一维或二维空间来对应一维时间，从而将总维度数减少到两维或三维，使可视化更加容易。“平面国的相对论”有助于我们理解自身宇宙中的相对论效应。

“The fourth dimension? That’s time, isn’t it?” It isn’t hard to imagine A Square’s rejoinder to such a question. He would turn the question back on the poser and remind him that in Flatland, the comparable response to the introduction to the concept of the third dimension is, “The third dimension? That’s time, isn’t it?” For beings whose universe has a spatial fourth dimension, the fifth dimension would be the one assigned to time, and in general we can expect that time will come in right after the dimensions that are reserved for space. For some modern physicists, there are ten dimensions which act like space, and the eleventh is time. The trouble is that when we treat time as a dimension, we do not expect it to act like the homogeneous interchangeable dimensions of space. There is a perfectly fine mathematics of space-time, but it is not one that Abbott is pointing to in Flatland. There we are asked to contemplate a fourth spatial dimension equivalent in all ways to the first three. As it happens, in order to introduce the geometry of space-time, almost all physics writers lower the dimension to that of one or two dimensions of space to go with one dimension of time, thereby reducing the total number of dimensions to two or three, allowing easier visualization. Relativity in Flatland helps us to understand relativistic effects in our own universe.

《平面国》的成书时间比阿尔伯特·爱因斯坦提出相对论早了整整一代人，在阿博特的时代，大多数思考维度的人关注的是空间的本质，而不是时空。（琼·理查兹新近出版的《数学幻象》是了解维多利亚时代英国几何学地位的一个很好的参考。）有几位作家认识到时间可以被视为与其他三个维度相似的维度，但又存在一些差异。赫尔曼·闵可夫斯基已经研究出以不同方式测量空间的一些后果，就像时间测量不同于空间测量一样。法国的埃德蒙·拉盖尔发展了一种四维球面几何学，每个球面可以用三个维度作为中心，另一个维度作为半径。但要判断两个球面是否相交，必须使用半径坐标表现为时间而非空间的公式。另一个涉及四变量的重要几何学是空间中的线几何学。我们可以通过指出线与一对水平面的交点来指定所有非水平线，并用两个坐标描述每个交点。数学家们很好地理解了这种四维几何，认为它们是抽象的概念，但对于物理上的第四维在各个方面都等同于公认的三维的概念，仍然存在着抵触情绪。正是对这种均匀四维空间进行可视化的挑战，构成了“平面国”的基础。

Flatland was written a full generation before Albert Einstein developed his theories of relativity, and most of the people who thought about dimensions in Abbott’s day were concerned with the nature of space rather than space-time. (A good reference for the place of geometry in Victorian England is the recent book Mathematical Visions by Joan Richards.) There were several writers who recognized that time could be treated as a dimension similar to the other three, but with certain differences. Hermann Minkowski had already worked out some of the consequences of measuring space in a way that treated one direction differently from the others, in the same way that time measurement is different from the measurement of space. Edmond Laguerre in France had developed a geometry of spheres that was four-dimensional in that each sphere could be specified by three dimensions for the center and one more dimension for the radius. But to tell whether or not two spheres intersected, it was necessary to use formulas in which the radius coordinate behaved like time rather than space. Another important geometry involving four variables was the geometry of lines in space. We can specify all non-horizontal lines by indicating the points where the line intersects a pair of horizontal planes, describing each of these points by two coordinates. Such four-dimensional geometries were well understood by mathematicians as abstract constructs, but resistance remained to the concept of a physical fourth dimension equivalent in every way to the accepted three dimensions. It is the challenge of visualizing such a homogeneous four-dimensional space that formed the basis of Flatland.

更高维度

HIGHER DIMENSIONS

值得注意的是，《平面国》并非专门探讨第四维。将第四维视为时间的弊端之一是，它往往会将事物止步于此。人们不太可能为了寻找空间的第四维而进入第五维（尽管玛德琳·英格尔的《时间的皱折》正是如此，作者将时空视为理所当然，并让强大的存在在五维虚空中找到捷径）。在《平面国》中，维度的数量是无限的，而故事的重点在于，起初无所不知的观察者球体最终受制于自身对维度的偏见，无法想象第三维以上的维度，就像四维生物一开始可能会怀疑五维或更高维度的存在一样。我们所有人都受制于自身维度的偏见。甚至连书的卷首插图也邀请读者去思考高达十维的世界。在巨大的云层周围透视绘制了这本书的名字。

It is important to note that Flatland is not specifically about the fourth dimension. One of the problems of thinking of the fourth dimension as time is that it tends to stop things at that stage. One is not likely to go on to a fifth dimension in order to find a fourth dimension of space (although that is precisely what happens in Madeleine L’Engle’s book A Wrinkle in Time, where the author takes space-time for granted and has her powerful beings taking shortcuts through a five-dimensional void). In Flatland, there is to be no limit on the number of dimensions, and indeed the point of the story is that the Sphere, at first an omniscent observer, is revealed as subject to his own dimensional prejudices, unable to conceive of a dimension beyond the third, as a four-dimensional being might begin by doubting the reality of anything of dimension five or higher. All of us are slaves to the prejudices of our own dimension. Even the frontispiece of the book invites readers to contemplate worlds of up to ten dimensions in the mammoth cloud around the perspective drawing of the name of the book.

奇怪的是，十维宇宙最近在量子物理学中颇为流行。人们很少尝试同时将如此多的维度形象化，但高维框架仍然提供了一种追踪大量变量的方法，其中一些变量非常小，以至于当我们专注于通常的三维空间时，它们可能会被忽略。另一个重要的模型采用了二十六维，这甚至超出了我们的形象化能力。尽管物理学家的最终目标是处理这些高维空间，但任何关于这个主题的通俗阐述都是从描述二维、三维和四维的类似物开始的，而且往往是指《平面国》中提出的类似物。

Curiously enough, it is a universe of ten spatial dimensions which has recently gained quite a bit of popularity in quantum physics. There is little attempt to visualize so many dimensions at once, but the framework of higher dimensions still provides a way of keeping track of a large number of variables, some so small that they can pass unnoticed when we concentrate on the usual three dimensions of space. Another important model employs twenty-six dimensions, even more beyond our powers of visualization. Even though the eventual aim of the physicists is to deal with spaces of these high dimensions, any popular exposition of the subject begins by describing analogues in two, three, and four dimensions, more often than not referring to the analogies presented in Flatland.

物理学中另一个出现高维空间的领域是空间曲率。几乎所有对这一概念的论述，要么直接引用《平面国》 ，要么作者或演讲者会提及荷兰物理教师戴奥尼斯·伯格于 1965 年撰写的续集《球面国》。在那本书中，《正方形》的后代踏上了漫长的旅程，发现他们的世界并非平坦的，而是弯曲成一个大球体的表面。同理，我们可以想象太空探险家们旅行到遥远的地方，最终发现我们自身所谓的平坦三维宇宙实际上就像球体表面一样有限。在这样的时刻，我们肯定会援引《平面国》的类比来帮助人们接受这种新的世界观。虽然严格来说，空间曲率的概念并不一定涉及我们所处空间弯曲成的高维空间，但这无疑是开始思考这个问题最自然的方式。杰夫·威克斯 (Jeff Weeks) 的《空间的形状》一书对这些概念进行了更深入的阐述。该书以“平面国”为起点，描述了拓扑复杂程度各异的二维世界，其形状类似甜甜圈、扭曲的莫比乌斯带或克莱因瓶。理解这些二维示例对于理解三维和四维空间形状的最新发展至关重要。想进一步了解这些主题以及其他使用维度类比的主题，请参阅鲁道夫·拉克 (Rudolf Rucker) 的《第四维度和几何、相对论与第四维度》 、AK·杜德尼 (A.K. Dewdney) 的《平面宇宙》以及我自己的著作《超越第三维度》。

Another area in which higher dimensions arise in physics is in the curvature of space. In almost any treatment of this concept, either Flatland is cited directly, or the writer or speaker will refer to Sphereland, the sequel written in 1965 by the Dutch physics teacher Dionys Burger. In that book, decendants of A Square set out on long journeys and discover that their world is not flat after all, but curved into the surface of a large sphere. In the same way we can imagine space explorers travelling so far that they determine that our own supposedly flat three-dimensional universe is in reality finite like the surface of a sphere. At such a moment we may be sure that the Flatland analogy will be invoked to help people come to terms with this new worldview. Although strictly speaking the concept of curvature of space does not necessarily involve a higher dimensional space that our space is curved into, this is undoubtedly the most natural way to begin thinking about this idea. A more thorough treatment of these concepts is found in The Shape of Space, by Jeff Weeks, which uses Flatland as a starting point and describes two-dimensional worlds of varying topological complexity, shaped like doughnuts or twisted Möbius bands or Klein bottles. Understanding such two-dimensional examples is crucial for appreciating the current developments in the shape of three- and four-dimensional space. For further reading on these and other topics using the dimensional analogy, see The Fourth Dimension and Geometry, Relativity, and the Fourth Dimension by Rudolf Rucker, The Planiverse by A. K. Dewdney and my own volume, Beyond the Third Dimension.

其他受益于高维数据集可视化最新进展的科学家是统计学家，尤其是从事探索性数据分析领域的统计学家。研究人员经常需要分析来自社会学调查或一系列物理或生物实验的大量数据。这类研究中的参数数量可能非常庞大，单个观察结果就会产生一串由十几个或更多数字组成的数据。在这些数据中寻找模式集合可以揭示隐藏的关系，使科学家能够在了解其他变量后预测某些变量的大小，并提出可以预测短期或长期行为的趋势。爱德华·塔夫特最近出版了一本关于数据可视化的书，名为《展望信息》（Envisioning Information），其第一章就是“逃离平面国”。1984年，在布朗大学举办的“平面国”百年纪念大会上，约翰和保罗·图基从A Square所能触及的数据可视化世界入手，介绍了探索性数据分析的全套技术。如今，中等规模的计算机软件使研究人员能够自由地操作多维数据集，将点云投影到三维或四维空间，然后在点集在空间中旋转时，或在数据集被切片以显示薄片中的点时，在图形屏幕上分析其模式。随着这样的测试板在数据集中移动，我们获得了有关整个集合中点分布的重要信息。平面国的切片技术至今仍是处理高维聚合体的最有力工具之一。

Other scientists who have profited by recent developments in visualization of data sets in high dimensions are the statisticians, especially those engaged in the field of exploratory data analysis. Researchers quite often have to analyze a mass of data from a sociological survey or a set of physical or biological experiments. The numbers of parameters in such investigations can be very large indeed, with a single observation leading to a string of a dozen or more numbers. Searching for patterns in such data collections can reveal hidden relationships, allowing scientists to predict the size of certain variables once others are known, and suggesting trends that can lead to predictions of short- or long-range behavior. A recent book on data visualization by Edward Tufte, Envisioning Information, has as its first chapter “Escaping from Flatland,” and at the centenary conference on Flatland at Brown University in 1984, John and Paul Tukey introduced a full range of techniques in exploratory data analysis by starting with the world of data visualization accessible to A Square. Software for computers of moderate size now enables researchers to manipulate multidimensional data sets with great freedom, projecting point clouds into three or four dimensions and then analyzing the patterns on a graphics screen as the collection of points is rotated in space, or as the data set is sliced to reveal the points lying in a thin slab. As such a test slab proceeds through the data set, we gain important information about the distribution of points in the whole collection. The slicing technique from Flatland still remains one of the most powerful tools for dealing with aggregates in higher dimensions.

切片技术在制图员绘制山区等高线图时也发挥着作用，即用阴影标出与两级之间区域对应的点。这项技术并不局限于使用二维切片分析三维数据，因为它在更高维度上也同样有效。如果空间中的每个点都被赋予一个表示其温度的第四个坐标，那么通过标出温度介于两个给定值之间的点，我们就能得到三维以上等高线图的类似物。这些相同的方法可以帮助数学家分析三个或更多变量的抽象函数的结构，进而可以作为分析越来越复杂的物理现象的模型。尽管这类方法在理论上已经可行多年，但直到最近，计算机才变得足够强大，能够有效地执行这些程序。现在，即使是相对较小的计算机也能生成等高线图，不久之后，我们就能轻松地将同样的方法应用于直接研究更高维度的对象。上个世纪数学家的梦想，被阿伯特有效地运用在他对人类理解和交流方式的探讨中，最终将触手可及。我们尚不清楚这种新的观察方式将如何彻底改变我们对几何及其应用的理解，但有一点是肯定的——任何想要充分利用可视化领域这些进展的人，都应该从阅读你手中的这本《平面国》开始。

The technique of slicing is also at work when a cartographer produces a contour map of a mountainous region, shading in the points that correspond to the region between two different levels. This technique does not have to stop with the analysis of three-dimensional data using two-dimensional slices since it works as well in higher dimensions. If each point in space is given a fourth coordinate indicating its temperature, then by indicating the points with temperature between two given values, we obtain an analogue of a contour map in more than three dimensions. These same approaches work to help mathematicians analyze the structure of abstract functions of three or more variables, which in turn can serve as models for the analysis of more and more complicated physical phenomena. Although such methods have been theoretically possible for many years, it is only in recent times that computers have become powerful enough to carry out the procedures effectively. Now even relatively small computers produce contour maps, and it will not be long before it will be easy to apply the same approach to the direct study of objects in higher dimensions. The dream of mathematicians of the last century, used so effectively by Abbott in his treatment of the ways we comprehend and the ways we communicate, will finally be within our grasp. We do not know all of the ways that this new way of seeing will change our approach to geometry and its applications, but one thing is sure-anyone who wants to make good use of these developments in visualization will begin by reading the book you now hold, Flatland.

第一部分 这个世界

Part I    This World

“要有耐心，因为世界很广阔。”

“Be patient, for the world is broad and wide.”

 

 

§1：论平面国的性质

§ 1: Of the Nature of Flatland

我把我们的世界称为平面国，并不是因为我们这样称呼它，而是为了让它的本质更清楚地呈现给你们，我快乐的读者，你们有幸生活在太空中。

I call our world Flatland, not because we call it so, but to make its nature clearer to you, my happy readers, who are privileged to live in Space.

想象一下，在一张巨大的纸上，直线、三角形、正方形、五边形、六边形以及其他图形并非固定在原地，而是在纸面上自由移动，既不能高高在上，也不能沉入纸面，就像影子一样——只有坚硬的边缘和发光的棱角——这样你就会对我的祖国和同胞有一个相当正确的认识。唉，几年前我应该说“我的宇宙”：但现在我的心胸已经开阔，能够以更高的视角看待事物。

Imagine a vast sheet of paper on which straight Lines, Triangles, Squares, Pentagons, Hexagons, and other figures, instead of remaining fixed in their places, move freely about, on or in the surface, but without the power of rising above or sinking below it, very much like shadows—only hard and with luminous edges—and you will then have a pretty correct notion of my country and countrymen. Alas, a few years ago, I should have said “my universe”: but now my mind has been opened to higher views of things.

在这样的国度里，你们会立刻意识到，根本不可能存在你们所谓的“立体”；但我敢说，你们会以为我们至少能凭视觉分辨出三角形、正方形以及其他像我描述的那样四处移动的图形。恰恰相反，我们什么也看不见，至少无法区分不同的图形。除了直线，我们什么也看不见，也看不到；至于这一点的必要性，我会很快证明。

In such a country, you will perceive at once that it is impossible that there should be anything of what you call a “solid” kind; but I dare say you will suppose that we could at least distinguish by sight the Triangles, Squares, and other figures, moving about as I have described them. On the contrary, we could see nothing of the kind, not at least so as to distinguish one figure from another. Nothing was visible, nor could be visible, to us, except Straight Lines; and the necessity of this I will speedily demonstrate.

把一枚硬币放在你太空中的一张桌子中间，俯身向下看。它会呈现出一个圆圈。

Place a penny on the middle of one of your tables in Space; and leaning over it, look down upon it. It will appear a circle.

但是现在，回到桌子的边缘，逐渐降低你的视线（从而使你自己越来越接近平面国居民的状态），你会发现这枚硬币在你的视野中变得越来越椭圆；最后，当你把你的目光准确地放在桌子的边缘时（这样，你实际上就成了一个平面国人），这枚硬币就不再是椭圆形了，在你看来，它变成了一条直线。

But now, drawing back to the edge of the table, gradually lower your eye (thus bringing yourself more and more into the condition of the inhabitants of Flatland), and you will find the penny becoming more and more oval to your view; and at last when you have placed your eye exactly on the edge of the table (so that you are, as it were, actually a Flatlander) the penny will then have ceased to appear oval at all, and will have become, so far as you can see, a straight line.

如果你用同样的方式处理三角形、正方形或任何其他从纸板上剪下来的图形，也会发生同样的情况。一旦你用眼睛贴着桌子边缘观察它，你会发现它不再是一个图形，而是变成了一条直线。以一个等边三角形为例——它代表着一位体面的商人。图1代表了你俯身俯视时看到的商人；图2和图3代表了你的眼睛接近或几乎与桌子齐平时看到的商人；而如果你的眼睛完全与桌子齐平（这就是我们在平面国看到的他），你看到的只是一条直线。

The same thing would happen if you were to treat in the same way a Triangle, or Square, or any other figure cut out of pasteboard. As soon as you look at it with your eye on the edge of the table, you will find that it ceases to appear to you a figure, and that it becomes in appearance a straight line. Take for example an equilateral Triangle-who represents with us a Tradesman of the respectable class. Fig. 1 represents the Tradesman as you would see him while you were bending over him from above; figs. 2 and 3 represent the Tradesman, as you would see him if your eye were close to the level, or all but on the level of the table; and if your eye were quite on the level of the table (and that is how we see him in Flatland) you would see nothing but a straight line.

我在太空国的时候听说，你们的水手们在穿越你们的海洋，辨认出地平线上某个遥远的岛屿或海岸时，也有着非常类似的体验。遥远的陆地或许有海湾、岬角，以及数量和范围都各异的起伏；然而，从远处看，你什么也看不见（除非你们的阳光明亮地照射在它们上面，通过光影显现出它们的起伏），水面上除了一条连续的灰色线条之外什么也看不见。

When I was in Spaceland I heard that your sailors have very similar experiences while they traverse your seas and discern some distant island or coast lying on the horizon. The far-off land may have bays, forelands, angles in and out to any number and extent; yet at a distance you see none of these (unless indeed your sun shines bright upon them, revealing the projections and retirements by means of light and shade), nothing but a grey unbroken line upon the water.

嗯，这就是我们在平面国遇到三角形或其他形状的熟人时看到的景象。由于我们身边没有太阳，也没有任何能形成阴影的光线，所以我们无法像在空间国那样看到。如果我们的朋友靠近我们，我们会看到他的线条变长；如果他离开我们，线条变短：但他看起来仍然像一条直线；无论他是三角形、正方形、五边形、六边形、圆形，无论什么形状——他看起来都是一条直线，别无其他。

Well, that is just what we see when one of our triangular or other acquaintances comes towards us in Flatland. As there is neither sun with us, nor any light of such a kind as to make shadows, we have none of the helps to the sight that you have in Spaceland. If our friend comes close to us we see his line becomes larger; if he leaves us it becomes smaller: but still he looks like a straight line; be he a Triangle, Square, Pentagon, Hexagon, Circle, what you will—a straight Line he looks and nothing else.

你或许会问，在如此不利的情况下，我们如何区分彼此的朋友？不过，当我描述一下“平面国”的居民时，这个自然而然的问题的答案会更加贴切和容易。暂时先搁置这个话题，先简单说说我们国家的气候和房屋。

You may perhaps ask how under these disadvantageous circumstances we are able to distinguish our friends from one another: but the answer to this very natural question will be more fitly and easily given when I come to describe the inhabitants of Flatland. For the present let me defer this subject, and say a word or two about the climate and houses in our country.

§2：平面国的气候和房屋

§ 2: Of the climate and houses in Flatland

正如你们一样，我们也一样，罗盘上有四个方位：北、南、东、西。

As with you, so also with us, there are four points of the compass North, South, East, and West.

由于没有太阳或其他天体，我们无法用通常的方法确定北方；但我们有自己的方法。根据自然法则，我们始终受到向南的引力；虽然在温带气候下，这种引力非常微弱——即使是身体健康的女人，也能毫不费力地向北行走几弗隆——但向南的引力所造成的阻碍，足以在地球上的大部分地区充当指南针。此外，雨水（每隔一段时间就会下）总是从北方而来，这又是一个额外的帮助；在城镇里，我们有房屋的指引，房屋的侧墙当然大多是南北走向的，这样屋顶就可以挡住来自北方的雨水。在没有房屋的乡村，树干可以起到某种引导的作用。总而言之，我们在确定方位方面并没有想象中那么困难。

There being no sun nor other heavenly bodies, it is impossible for us to determine the North in the usual way; but we have a method of our own. By a Law of Nature with us, there is a constant attraction to the South; and, although in temperate climates this is very slight—so that even a Woman in reasonable health can journey several furlongs northward without much difficulty—yet the hampering effect of the southward attraction is quite sufficient to serve as a compass in most parts of our earth. Moreover the rain (which falls at stated intervals) coming always from the North, is an additional assistance; and in the towns we have the guidance of the houses, which of course have their side-walls running for the most part North and South, so that the roofs may keep off the rain from the North. In the country, where there are no houses, the trunks of the trees serve as some sort of guide. Altogether, we have not so much difficulty as might be expected in determining our bearings.

然而，在我们气候较为温和的地区，几乎感觉不到向南的吸引力，有时我会走在一片完全荒凉的平原上，那里既没有房屋，也没有树木为我指引方向，我偶尔会被迫停留在原地我一连几个小时等到雨停才继续赶路。对于体弱多病、年老体弱的女性，尤其是娇弱的女性，吸引力的影响远大于对健壮的男性。所以，如果你在街上遇到一位女士，一定要让她走北边，这是一种教养的体现——在你身体状况不佳，又身处难以分辨南北的气候条件下，要在短时间内做到这一点绝非易事。

Yet in our more temperate regions, in which the southward attraction is hardly felt, walking sometimes in a perfectly desolate plain where there have been no houses nor trees to guide me, I have been occasionally compelled to remain stationary for hours together, waiting till the rain came before continuing my journey. On the weak and aged, and especially on delicate Females, the force of attraction tells much more heavily than on the robust of the Male Sex, so that it is a point of breeding, if you meet a Lady in the street always to give her the North side of the way—by no means an easy thing to do always at short notice when you are in rude health and in a climate where it is difficult to tell your North from your South.

我们的房子里没有窗户：因为光线照进屋内，也照出屋外，白天黑夜，无论何时何地，都是一样的，我们却不知道从何而来。古时，我们的学者们常常研究一个有趣的问题：“光的起源是什么？”他们曾反复尝试解答这个问题，但结果却只是把我们的疯人院挤满了那些自以为是的人。因此，立法机关曾试图通过对这类研究征收重税来间接压制它们，但徒劳无功。到了近代，立法机关彻底禁止了这类研究。我——唉，在平面国，只有我——现在非常清楚这个神秘问题的真正答案；但我的知识却无法让我的任何一位同胞理解；我，作为唯一掌握空间真理和从三维世界引入光的理论的人——却被嘲笑，仿佛我是疯子中的疯子！但这些令人痛苦的离题之事暂时告一段落：让我回到我们的家中。

Windows there are none in our houses: for the light comes to us alike in our homes and out of them, by day and by night, equally at all times and in all places, whence we know not. It was in old days, with our learned men, an interesting and oft-investigated question, “What is the origin of light?” and the solution of it has been repeatedly attempted, with no other result than to crowd our lunatic asylums with the would-be solvers. Hence, after fruitless attempts to suppress such investigations indirectly by making them liable to a heavy tax, the Legislature, in comparatively recent times, absolutely prohibited them. I—alas I alone in Flatland—know now only too well the true solution of this mysterious problem; but my knowledge cannot be made intelligible to a single one of my countrymen; and I am mocked at-I, the sole possessor of the truths of Space and of the theory of the introduction of Light from the world of Three Dimensions-as if I were the maddest of the mad! But a truce to these painful digressions: let me return to our houses.

最常见的房屋建筑形式是五边形或五角形，如附图所示。北侧RO和OF构成屋顶，大部分没有门；东侧有一扇小门，供妇女使用；西侧有一扇更大的门，供男子使用；南侧或楼层通常没有门。

The most common form for the construction of a house is five-sided or pentagonal, as in the annexed figure. The two Northern sides RO, OF, constitute the roof, and for the most part have no doors; on the East is a small door for the Women; on the West a much larger one for the Men; the South side or floor is usually doorless.

方形和三角形房屋是不允许的，原因如下。正方形的角（尤其是等边三角形的角）比五边形的角尖得多，而无生命物体（例如房屋）的线条比男人和女人的线条更暗淡，因此，方形或三角形房屋的尖角可能会对一个粗心大意或心不在焉的旅行者造成严重伤害，这很危险：因此，早在公元11世纪，三角形房屋就被法律普遍禁止，唯一的例外是防御工事、火药库、兵营和其他国家建筑，公众不应在未经谨慎的情况下接近这些建筑。

Square and triangular houses are not allowed, and for this reason. The angles of a Square (and still more those of an equilateral Triangle) being much more pointed than those of a Pentagon, and the lines of inanimate objects (such as houses) being dimmer than the lines of Men and Women, it follows that there is no little danger lest the points of a square or triangular house residence might do serious injury to an inconsiderate or perhaps absentminded traveller suddenly running against them: and therefore, as early as the eleventh century of our era, triangular houses were universally forbidden by Law, the only exceptions being fortifications, powder-magazines, barracks, and other state buildings, which it is not desirable that the general public should approach without circumspection.

当时，尽管征收了一项特殊税，方形房屋仍然在各地被允许建造。但大约三个世纪后，法律规定，在所有人口超过一万的城镇，五边形的房屋角度是保证公共安全所允许的最小房屋角度。良好的社会意识支持了立法机构的努力；如今，即使在乡村，五边形建筑也取代了其他所有建筑。只有在一些非常偏远落后的农业地区，古物学家偶尔才能发现方形房屋。

At this period, square houses were still everywhere permitted, though discouraged by a special tax. But, about three centuries afterwards, the Law decided that in all towns containing a population above ten thousand, the angle of a Pentagon was the smallest house-angle that could be allowed consistently with the public safety. The good sense of the community has seconded the efforts of the Legislature; and now, even in the country, the pentagonal construction has superseded every other. It is only now and then in some very remote and backward agricultural district that an antiquarian may still discover a square house.

§3：关于平面国的居民

§ 3: Concerning the Inhabitants of Flatland

平面国的成年居民，其最大身长或身宽估计约为十一英寸。十二英寸可视为最大值。

The greatest length or breadth of a full-grown inhabitant of Flatland may be estimated at about eleven of your inches. Twelve inches may be regarded as a maximum.

我们的女人是直线条。

Our Women are Straight Lines.

我们的士兵和最底层的工人是三角形，两条边相等，每条边约十一英寸长，底边或第三边非常短（通常不超过半英寸），以至于它们的顶点形成一个非常尖锐可怕的角。事实上，当它们的底边是最不规则的类型（不超过八分之一英寸长）时，它们几乎与直线或女人难以区分；它们的顶点非常尖锐。在我们这里，就像在你们这里​​一样，这些三角形被称为等腰三角形，以区别于其他三角形；在接下来的篇幅中，我将用这个名字来指代它们。

Our Soldiers and Lowest Class of Workmen are Triangles with two equal sides, each about eleven inches long, and a base or third side so short (often not exceeding half an inch) that they form at their vertices a very sharp and formidable angle. Indeed when their bases are of the most degraded type (not more than the eighth part of an inch in size) they can hardly be distinguished from Straight Lines or Women; so extremely pointed are their vertices. With us, as with you, these Triangles are distinguished from others by being called Isosceles; and by this name I shall refer to them in the following pages.

我们的中产阶级由等边三角形或等边三角形组成。

Our Middle Class consists of Equilateral or Equal-sided Triangles.

我们的专业人士和绅士是正方形（我本人就属于这一类）和五边形或五边形。

Our Professional Men and Gentlemen are Squares (to which class I myself belong) and Five-sided figures or Pentagons.

再往上是贵族，贵族的等级有多个，从六边形开始，边数逐渐增加，直到获得多边形或多边形的尊称。最后，当边数变得非常多，而边本身又非常小，以至于无法与圆形区分时，他们就被纳入圆形或祭司阶层；这是所有阶层中最高的。

Next above these come the Nobility, of whom there are several degrees, beginning at Six-sided Figures, or Hexagons, and from thence rising in the number of their sides till they receive the honourable title of Polygonal, or many-sided. Finally when the number of the sides becomes so numerous, and the sides themselves so small, that the figure cannot be distinguished from a circle, he is included in the Circular or Priestly order; and this is the highest class of all.

按照我们的自然法则，男孩的边数应该比父亲多一条，这样每一代人的发展和高贵程度（通常）都会上升一级。因此，正方形的儿子是五边形；五边形的儿子是六边形；以此类推。

It is a Law of Nature with us that a male child shall have one more side than his father, so that each generation shall rise (as a rule) one step in the scale of development and nobility. Thus the son of a Square is a Pentagon; the son of a Pentagon, a Hexagon; and so on.

但这条规则并不总是适用于商人，更不用说士兵和工人了；他们确实很难被称为人形，因为它们的边并非全都相等。因此，自然律对他们不成立；等腰三角形（即两条边相等的三角形）的儿子仍然是等腰三角形。然而，即使是等腰三角形，也并非完全没有希望，他的后代最终能够摆脱这种堕落的境遇。因为，在长期的军事胜利或勤奋熟练的劳动之后，通常发现工匠和士兵阶层中较为聪明的人，他们的第三条边或底边会略微增加，而另外两条边会缩短。这些下层阶级中较为聪明的成员的子女之间通婚（由祭司安排），通常会生出更接近等边三角形类型的后代。

But this rule applies, not always to the Tradesmen, and still less often to the Soldiers, and to the Workmen; who indeed can hardly be said to deserve the name of human Figures, since they have not all their sides equal. With them therefore the Law of Nature does not hold; and the son of an Isosceles (i.e. a Triangle with two sides equal) remains Isosceles still. Nevertheless, all hope is not shut out, even from the Isosceles, that his posterity may ultimately rise above his degraded condition. For, after a long series of military successes, or diligent and skilful labours, it is generally found that the more intelligent among the Artisan and Soldier classes manifest a slight increase of their third side or base, and a shrinkage of the two other sides. Intermarriages (arranged by the Priests) between the sons and daughters of these more intellectual members of the lower classes generally result in an offspring approximating still more to the type of the Equal-sided Triangle.

与数量众多的等腰三角形婴儿相比，真正可证实的等腰三角形婴儿出生的案例却少之又少。*这样的婴儿出生，不仅需要一系列精心安排的通婚，还需要未来等腰三角形婴儿的祖先长期坚持节俭和自制，以及耐心、系统、持续地发展等腰三角形婴儿的智力。

Rarely—in proportion to the vast numbers of Isosceles births—is a genuine and certifiable Equal-sided Triangle produced from Isosceles parents.* Such a birth requires, as its antecedents, not only a series of carefully arranged intermarriages, but also a long-continued exercise of frugality and self-control on the part of the would-be ancestors of the coming Equilateral, and a patient, systematic, and continuous development of the Isosceles intellect through many generations.

在我们国家，等腰三角形父母孕育出一个真正的等边三角形，是方圆数弗隆范围内人们欢庆的盛事。经过卫生和社会委员会的严格检查，如果婴儿被认定为“正等边三角形”，就会举行庄严的仪式，被纳入等边三角形的范畴。之后，他会立即被从骄傲而又悲伤的父母身边带走，被某个没有子女的等边三角形收养。收养者必须发誓，从今以后绝不允许孩子回到原来的家，甚至不许他再去看望亲戚，以免这个刚刚发育的婴儿，在无意识的模仿下，再次回到遗传的水平。

The birth of a True Equilateral Triangle from Isosceles parents is the subject of rejoicing in our country for many furlongs round. After a strict examination conducted by the Sanitary and Social Board, the infant, if certified as Regular, is with solemn ceremonial admitted into the class of Equilaterals. He is then immediately taken from his proud yet sorrowing parents and adopted by some childless Equilateral, who is bound by oath never to permit the child henceforth to enter his former home or so much as to look upon his relations again, for fear lest the freshly developed organism may, by force of unconscious imitation, fall back again into his hereditary level.

农奴出身的祖先中偶尔会出现等腰三角形，这不仅受到贫穷农奴的欢迎，认为这是给他们单调肮脏的生活带来一丝光明和希望，而且也受到广大贵族的欢迎；因为所有上层阶级都很清楚，这些罕见的现象虽然对使他们自己的特权庸俗化没有多大作用，但却是阻止下层革命的最有用的屏障。

The occasional emergence of an Isosceles from the ranks of his serf-born ancestors, is welcomed not only by the poor serfs themselves, as a gleam of light and hope shed upon the monotonous squalor of their existence, but also by the Aristocracy at large; for all the higher classes are well aware that these rare phenomena, while they do little or nothing to vulgarise their own privileges, serve as a most useful barrier against revolution from below.

如果这些锐角暴徒毫无例外地完全丧失希望和野心，他们或许会在众多叛乱事件中找到领袖，这些领袖能够利用他们的优势人数和力量，甚至连“圆圈”的智慧也无法抵挡。然而，造物主的明智法则是：随着工人阶级智力、知识和所有美德的增长，他们的锐角（这让他们身体上变得可怕）也会随之增长，最终接近于无害的等边三角形的锐角。因此，即使是最野蛮、最可怕的士兵，智力的匮乏程度几乎与女人不相上下——我们发现，随着他们运用巨大穿透力所需的智力的增强，他们的穿透力本身也在减弱。

Had the acute-angled rabble been all, without exception, absolutely destitute of hope and of ambition, they might have found leaders in some of their many seditious outbreaks, so able as to render their superior numbers and strength too much for the wisdom even of the Circles. But a wise ordinance of Nature has decreed that in proportion as the working-classes increase in intelligence, knowledge, and all virtue, in that same proportion their acute angle (which makes them physically terrible) shall increase also and approximate to the harmless angle of the Equilateral Triangle. Thus, in the most brutal and formidable of the soldier class creatures almost on a level with women in their lack of intelligence—it is found that, as they wax in the mental ability necessary to employ their tremendous penetrating power to advantage, so do they wane in the power of penetration itself.

“补偿法则”多么令人钦佩！这多么完美地证明了平面国各州贵族政体的自然适应性，甚至可以说是神圣的起源！通过明智地运用这一自然法则，多边形和圆形几乎总能利用人类心灵中不可抑制的无限希望，将叛乱扼杀在萌芽状态。艺术也为法律和秩序提供了助力。通常情况下，只要州医生稍微人为地压缩或扩张一下，就能让一些较为聪明的叛乱领袖变得完全正规，并立即将他们纳入特权阶层；而更多仍处于劣势的人，在最终被封为贵族的前景的诱惑下，被引诱进入州立医院，在那里他们被终身监禁，享受着光荣的待遇；只有一两个较为顽固、愚蠢、极其不正规的人会被处决。

How admirable is the Law of Compensation! And how perfect a proof of the natural fitness and, I may almost say, the divine origin of the aristocratic constitution of the States of Flatland! By a judicious use of this Law of Nature, the Polygons and Circles are almost always able to stifle sedition in its very cradle, taking advantage of the irrepressible and boundless hopefulness of the human mind. Art also comes to the aid of Law and Order. It is generally found possible—by a little artificial compression or expansion on the part of the State physicians—to make some of the more intelligent leaders of a rebellion perfectly Regular, and to admit them at once into the privileged classes; a much larger number, who are still below the standard, allured by the prospect of being ultimately ennobled, are induced to enter the State Hospitals, where they are kept in honourable confinement for life; one or two alone of the more obstinate, foolish, and hopelessly irregular are led to execution.

于是，等腰三角形的可怜乌合之众，既无计划，又无领袖，要么毫无抵抗地被他们那一小群同胞所制服，而这些同胞正是圆顶部落为应对此类紧急情况而雇佣的；要么，更常见的情况是，圆顶部落巧妙地在他们中间煽动嫉妒和猜疑，煽动他们互相开战，最终死于彼此的角下。我们的史册中记录了至少一百二十次叛乱，此外还有二百三十五次小规模的暴乱；而这些叛乱都以这样的方式结束。

Then the wretched rabble of the Isosceles, planless and leaderless, are either transfixed without resistance by the small body of their brethren whom the Chief Circle keeps in pay for emergencies of this kind; or else, more often, by means of jealousies and suspicions skilfully fomented among them by the Circular party, they are stirred to mutual warfare, and perish by one another’s angles. No less than one hundred and twenty rebellions are recorded in our annals, besides minor outbreaks numbered at two hundred and thirty-five; and they have all ended thus.

* “需要什么证明？”一位太空国度的批评者可能会问：“生出一个正方形的儿子，难道不就是大自然本身的证明，证明父亲的等边性吗？”我回答说，任何地位的女士都不会娶一个未经证实的三角形。正方形的后代有时是由略微不规则的三角形产生的：但几乎在所有此类情况下，第一代的不规则性都会影响到第三代；第三代要么无法达到五边形的等级，要么又回到了三角形。

* “What need of a certificate?” a Spaceland critic may ask: “Is not the procreation of a Square Son a certificate from Nature herself, proving the Equal-sidedness of the Father?” I reply that no Lady of any position will marry an uncertified Triangle. Square offspring has sometimes resulted from a slightly Irregular Triangle: but in almost every such case the Irregularity of the first generation is visited on the third; which either fails to attain the Pentagonal rank, or relapses to the Triangular.

§4：关于妇女

§ 4: Concerning the Women

如果说士兵类的尖角三角形令人望而生畏，那么不难推断，女性类的三角形也同样令人望而生畏。因为，如果士兵是楔子，那么女性就是针；可以说，所有三角形都尖锐，至少在两端是如此。凭借这种可以随意让自己几乎隐形的力量，你会发现平面国中的女性是一种绝对不能被戏弄的生物。

If our highly pointed Triangles of the Soldier class are formidable, it may be readily inferred that far more formidable are our Women. For, if a Soldier is a wedge, a Woman is a needle; being, so to speak, all point, at least at the two extremities. Add to this the power of making herself practically invisible at will, and you will perceive that a Female in Flatland, is a creature by no means to be trifled with.

不过，或许我的一些年轻读者会问，平面国的女人是如何让自己隐形的。我想，这应该不言而喻。然而，即使是最不加思考的人，几句话也能明白。

But here, perhaps, some of my younger Readers may ask how a woman in Flatland can make herself invisible. This ought, I think, to be apparent without any explanation. However, a few words will make it clear to the most unreflecting.

把一根针放在桌子上。然后，你的眼睛与桌面齐平，从侧面看它，你能看到它的全长；但从它的末端看，你只会看到一个点：它几乎隐形了。我们的一位女性也是如此。当她侧身面向我们时，我们看见她就像一条直线；当她眼睛或嘴巴所在的末端——在我们看来，这两个器官是相同的——与我们的视线相通时，我们只会看到一个非常有光泽的点；但当她的背部呈现在我们眼前时，由于光泽度很低，几乎像无生命物体一样暗淡——她的后肢就像一顶隐形帽。

Place a needle on a table. Then, with your eye on the level of the table, look at it side-ways, and you see the whole length of it; but look at it end-ways, and you see nothing but a point: it has become practically invisible. Just so is it with one of our Women. When her side is turned towards us, we see her as a straight line; when the end containing her eye or mouth—for with us these two organs are identical—is the part that meets our eye, then we see nothing but a highly lustrous point; but when the back is presented to our view, then—being only sub-lustrous, and, indeed, almost as dim as an inanimate object—her hinder extremity serves her as a kind of Invisible Cap.

我们女性所面临的危险，如今在太空国度，即使是最卑微的人，也必须一览无余。如果中产阶级体面的三角形角落也存在危险；如果撞上工人会划出一道口子；如果与军官相撞会造成重伤；如果普通士兵的顶点轻轻一碰就会有生命危险——那么，与女性发生冲突，除了立即遭到彻底的毁灭，还能是什么呢？而当女性隐形，或者只在肉眼可见的暗淡无光的点上显现时，即使是最谨慎的人，也很难始终避免冲突！

The dangers to which we are exposed from our Women must now be manifest to the meanest capacity in Spaceland. If even the angle of a respectable Triangle in the middle class is not without its dangers; if to run against a Working Man involves a gash; if collision with an Officer of the military class necessitates a serious wound; if a mere touch from the vertex of a Private Soldier brings with it danger of death;—what can it be to run against a Woman, except absolute and immediate destruction? And when a Woman is invisible, or visible only as a dim sub-lustrous point, how difficult must it be, even for the most cautious, always to avoid collision!

为了尽量减少这种危险，平面国各州在不同时期颁布了许多法令；在南方和气候较温和的地区，地心引力较大，人体更容易受到偶然和不自觉的运动，因此有关妇女的法律自然要严格得多。不过，可以从以下摘要中大致了解该法典：

Many are the enactments made at different times in the different States of Flatland, in order to minimize this peril; and in the Southern and less temperate climates, where the force of gravitation is greater, and human beings more liable to casual and involuntary motions, the Laws concerning Women are naturally much more stringent. But a general view of the Code may be obtained from the following summary:—

1. 每栋房屋的东侧都应有一个入口，仅供女性使用；所有女性都应“以得体和尊重的方式”进入该入口*，而不得从男门或西门进入。

1. Every house shall have one entrance in the Eastern side, for the use of Females only; by which all females shall enter “in a becoming and respectful manner”* and not by the Men’s or Western door.

2. 任何女性不得在任何公共场所行走而不不断发出“和平呼喊”，否则将被处以死刑。

2. No Female shall walk in any public place without continually keeping up her Peace-cry, under penalty of death.

3. 任何女性，经正式证明患有圣维特斯舞蹈症、癫痫、伴有剧烈打喷嚏的慢性感冒或任何需要不自主运动的疾病，都应立即被消灭。

3. Any Female, duly certified to be suffering from St. Vitus’s Dance, fits, chronic cold accompanied by violent sneezing, or any disease necessitating involuntary motions, shall be instantly destroyed.

有些州还附加了一条法律，禁止女性在任何公共场所行走或站立，否则须不停地左右摇晃背部，以示对身后之人的注意，违者处以死刑；另一些州则规定，女性出行时，必须由其儿子、仆人或丈夫跟随；还有一些州则将女性完全禁锢在家中，除非宗教节日。然而，我们最睿智的学界人士或政治家们发现，对女性的限制增多，不仅会导致种族衰弱和种族灭绝，还会导致家庭谋杀案增多，以至于一个州因制定过于严格的法典而得不偿失。

In some of the States there is an additional Law forbidding Females, under penalty of death, from walking or standing in any public place without moving their backs constantly from right to left so as to indicate their presence to those behind them; others oblige a Woman, when travelling, to be followed by one of her sons, or servants, or by her husband; others confine Women altogether in their houses except during the religious festivals. But it has been found by the wisest of our Circles or Statesmen that the multiplication of restrictions on Females tends not only to the debilitation and diminution of the race, but also to the increase of domestic murders to such an extent that a State loses more than it gains by a too prohibitive Code.

因为每当妇女们因为家中禁锢或外出受阻的规章制度而脾气暴躁时，她们很容易将怒气发泄在丈夫和孩子身上；在气候不太温和的地方，有时一个村庄的所有男性人口会在一两个小时内因女性同时爆发而全部丧生。因此，上述三项法律对于管理较为完善的州来说已经足够，可以作为我们《妇女法典》的粗略范例。

For whenever the temper of the Women is thus exasperated by confinement at home or hampering regulations abroad, they are apt to vent their spleen upon their husbands and children; and in the less temperate climates the whole male population of a village has been sometimes destroyed in one or two hours of a simultaneous female outbreak. Hence the Three Laws, mentioned above, suffice for the better regulated States, and may be accepted as a rough exemplification of our Female Code.

毕竟，我们主要的保障并非来自立法机构，而是来自女性自身的利益。因为，尽管她们可以通过逆行瞬间致人死亡，但除非她们能立即将刺痛的肢体从受害者挣扎的身体上抽离，否则她们自身脆弱的身体也很容易被击碎。
