After all, our principal safeguard is found, not in Legislature, but in the interests of the Women themselves. For, although they can inflict instantaneous death by a retrograde movement, yet unless they can at once disengage their stinging extremity from the struggling body of their victim, their own frail bodies are liable to be shattered.

时尚的力量也站在我们这边。我指出，在一些文明程度较低的州，任何女性在公共场所站立都必须左右摇动背部。自古以来，在所有治理良好的州，这种做法在那些自诩有教养的女性中都很普遍。任何州都认为，立法强制执行本该是自然本能的举动是一种耻辱，而这其实是每个受人尊敬的女性的天性。我们圆形阶级的女士们背部有节奏地（如果我可以这么说的话）起伏，受到普通等边形的妻子的羡慕和模仿，她们除了像钟摆的滴答声一样单调地摆动之外，什么也做不了；而等边形的规律滴答声也同样受到进步而有抱负的等腰三角形的妻子的钦佩和模仿，在等腰三角形的女性中，任何形式的“背部运动”都尚未成为生活的必需品。因此，在每一个有地位和地位的家庭中，“退缩运动”就像时间本身一样普遍；而这些家庭中的丈夫和儿子至少可以免受无形的攻击。

The power of Fashion is also on our side. I pointed out that in some less civilised States no female is suffered to stand in any public place without swaying her back from right to left. This practice has been universal among ladies of any pretensions to breeding in all well-governed States, as far back as the memory of Figures can reach. It is considered a disgrace to any State that legislation should have to enforce what ought to be, and is in every respectable female, a natural instinct. The rhythmical and, if I may so say, well-modulated undulation of the back in our ladies of Circular rank is envied and imitated by the wife of a common Equilateral, who can achieve nothing beyond a mere monotonous swing, like the ticking of a pendulum; and the regular tick of the Equilateral is no less admired and copied by the wife of the progressive and aspiring Isosceles, in the females of whose family no “back-motion” of any kind has become as yet a necessity of life. Hence, in every family of position and consideration, “back motion” is as prevalent as time itself; and the husbands and sons in these households enjoy immunity at least from invisible attacks.

这并不意味着我们的女人缺乏感情。但不幸的是，在脆弱的性别中，一时的激情压倒了其他一切。这当然是她们不幸的体型所导致的必然结果。因为她们没有角，在这方面甚至比等腰三角形中最低的三角形还要差，因此她们完全缺乏智力，既没有反思、判断力，也没有深谋远虑，几乎没有记忆力。因此，在她们暴怒之时，她们不记得任何权利，也不承认任何区别。我的确知道一个案例，一个女人杀了她全家，半小时后，当她的怒火平息，碎片被扫走后，她才问她的丈夫和孩子们怎么样了！

Not that it must be for a moment supposed that our Women are destitute of affection. But unfortunately the passion of the moment predominates, in the Frail Sex, over every other consideration. This is, of course, a necessity arising from their unfortunate conformation. For as they have no pretensions to an angle, being inferior in this respect to the very lowest of the Isosceles, they are consequently wholly devoid of brainpower, and have neither reflection, judgment nor forethought, and hardly any memory. Hence, in their fits of fury, they remember no claims and recognise no distinctions. I have actually known a case where a Woman has exterminated her whole household, and half an hour afterwards, when her rage was over and the fragments swept away, has asked what has become of her husband and children!

显然，只要女人还能转身，就不会被激怒。当你把她们关在房间里——而她们的住所的设计初衷就是剥夺她们的这种权利——你想说什么做什么就说什么；因为那时她们已经完全无力再做坏事了，几分钟后她们就不会再想起此刻她们可能正用死亡威胁你的事情，也不会想起你为了平息她们的怒火而不得不做出的承诺。

Obviously then a Woman is not to be irritated as long as she is in a position where she can turn round. When you have them in their apartments—which are constructed with a view to denying them that power—you can say and do what you like; for they are then wholly impotent for mischief, and will not remember a few minutes hence the incident for which they may be at this moment threatening you with death, nor the promises which you may have found it necessary to make in order to pacify their fury.

总体而言，除了军人阶层的底层，我们的家庭关系还算融洽。在军人阶层中，丈夫们缺乏机智和判断力，有时会造成难以言喻的灾难。这些鲁莽的家伙过于依赖锐角这种进攻性武器，而非理智和适时模仿这种防御手段，常常忽视女性房间的既定结构，或在户外用不恰当的言辞激怒妻子，而且她们拒绝立即收回这些言辞。此外，他们对字面真理的麻木不仁和漠不关心，使得他们不愿做出那些慷慨的承诺，而那些更明智的圆腰三角形可以用这些承诺瞬间安抚他的配偶。结果就是大屠杀；然而，这并非没有好处，因为它消灭了更残暴、更麻烦的等腰三角形；在我们的许多圈子里，女性体型偏瘦的破坏性被视为抑制人口过剩和将革命扼杀在萌芽状态的众多天意安排之一。

On the whole we got on pretty smoothly in our domestic relations, except in the lower strata of the Military Classes. There the want of tact and discretion on the part of the husbands produces at times indescribable disasters. Relying too much on the offensive weapons of their acute angles instead of the defensive organs of good sense and seasonable simulations, these reckless creatures too often neglect the prescribed construction of the Women’s apartments, or irritate their wives by ill-advised expressions out of doors, which they refuse immediately to retract. Moreover a blunt and stolid regard for literal truth indisposes them to make those lavish promises by which the more judicious Circle can in a moment pacify his consort. The result is massacre; not however without its advantages, as it eliminates the more brutal and troublesome of the Isosceles; and by many of our Circles the destructiveness of the Thinner Sex is regarded as one among many providential arrangements for suppressing redundant population, and nipping Revolution in the bud.

然而，即使在我们这些秩序最完善、最接近圆形的家庭里，我也不能说家庭生活的理想像你们在太空国那样崇高。那里很和平，至少可以称之为没有屠杀，但品味和兴趣的和谐程度必然很低；圆形的谨慎智慧以牺牲家庭舒适为代价，换来了安全。在每个圆形或多边形家庭里，自古以来就有一种习惯——现在在我们上层阶级的女性中，这已经成为一种本能——母亲和女儿应该时刻关注着她们的丈夫和……他的男性朋友；而对于出身名门的女士来说，背弃自己的丈夫会被视为一种预兆，会丧失地位。但是，正如我很快会展示的，这种习俗虽然有安全的优势，但也并非没有缺点。

Yet even in our best regulated and most approximately circular families I cannot say that the ideal of family life is so high as with you in Spaceland. There is peace, in so far as the absence of slaughter may be called by that name, but there is necessarily little harmony of tastes or pursuits; and the cautious wisdom of the Circles has ensured safety at the cost of domestic comfort. In every Circular or Polygonal household it has been a habit from time immemorial—and has now become a kind of instinct among the women of our higher classes—that the mothers and daughters should constantly keep their eyes and mouths towards their husband and his male friends; and for a lady in a family of distinction to turn her back upon her husband would be regarded as a kind of portent, involving loss of status. But, as I shall soon shew, this custom, though it has the advantage of safety, is not without disadvantages.

在工人或受人尊敬的商人家中——妻子可以背对着丈夫，忙于家务——至少会有片刻的宁静，妻子的身影若隐若现，听不见也听不见，只有持续不断的“和好”的低语声；但在上流社会的家中，却常常得不到安宁。在那里，滔滔不绝的嘴巴和敏锐的目光总是投向一家之主；光明本身并不比女人滔滔不绝的话语更持久。足以避免女人刺痛的机智和技巧，却无法堵住女人的嘴；由于妻子完全无话可说，也没有任何智慧、理智或良心可以阻止她说话，不少愤世嫉俗者声称，他们宁愿承受致命却又听不见的刺痛，也不愿承受女人那一声安全的洪亮。

In the house of the Working Man or respectable Tradesman—where the wife is allowed to turn her back upon her husband, while pursuing her household avocations—there are at least intervals of quiet, when the wife is neither seen nor heard, except for the humming sound of the continuous Peace-cry; but in the homes of the upper classes there is too often no peace. There the voluble mouth and bright penetrating eye are ever directed towards the Master of the household; and light itself is not more persistent than the stream of feminine discourse. The tact and skill which suffice to avert a Woman’s sting are unequal to the task of stopping a Woman’s mouth; and as the wife has absolutely nothing to say, and absolutely no constraint of wit, sense, or conscience to prevent her from saying it, not a few cynics have been found to aver that they prefer the danger of the death-dealing but inaudible sting to the safe sonorousness of a Woman’s other end.

对于我《空间国》的读者来说，我们女性的境况或许显得真正可悲，事实也的确如此。等腰三角形中最低等的男性或许期待着自己的角度有所改善，并最终提升其整个低下阶层；但没有哪个女性会对自己的性别抱有这样的希望。“一日为女人，终生为女人”是自然法则；而进化法则本身似乎也因对女性不利而悬而未决。然而，至少我们可以钦佩那明智的预判，它注定了她们没有希望，也就没有记忆可以回想，也没有预见到那些既是她们生存的必然，也是平面国构成基础的苦难和屈辱。

To my readers in Spaceland the condition of our Women may seem truly deplorable, and so indeed it is. A Male of the lowest type of the Isosceles may look forward to some improvement of his angle, and to the ultimate elevation of the whole of his degraded caste; but no Woman can entertain such hopes for her sex. “Once a Woman, always a Woman” is a Decree of Nature; and the very Laws of Evolution seem suspended in her disfavour. Yet at least we can admire the wise Prearrangement which has ordained that, as they have no hopes, so they shall have no memory to recall, and no forethought to anticipate, the miseries and humiliations which are at once a necessity of their existence and the basis of the constitution of Flatland.

*当我在太空国度时，我了解到你们的一些祭司圈子同样为村民、农民和公立学校的教师设有单独的入口（《旁观者》，1884 年 9 月，第 1255 页），以便他们可以“以得体和尊重的方式接近”。

* When I was in Spaceland I understood that some of your Priestly Circles have in the same way a separate entrance for Villagers, Farmers, and Teachers of Board Schools (Spectator, Sept. 1884, p. 1255) that they may “approach in a becoming and respectful manner.”

§5：关于我们彼此识别的方法

§ 5: Of our methods of recognizing one another

您，既能感知光，又能感知阴影；您，天生一双眼睛，懂得透视，沉醉于各种色彩的享受；您，能够真实地看到一个角度，能够在三维空间的幸福区域中思考一个圆的完整周长——我该如何向您解释，我们在平面国中彼此辨认形状时所经历的极大困难呢？

You, who are blessed with shade as well as light, you who are gifted with two eyes, endowed with a knowledge of perspective, and charmed with the enjoyment of various colours, you, who can actually see an angle, and contemplate the complete circumference of a Circle in the happy region of the Three Dimensions—how shall I make clear to you the extreme difficulty which we in Flatland experience in recognizing one another’s configuration?

回想一下我上面告诉你的。平面国里的所有生物，无论有生命还是无生命，无论其形态如何，在我们看来，都呈现出相同或近乎相同的外观。即直线。那么，在所有看起来都一样的地方，如何区分一条线与另一条线呢？

Recall what I told you above. All beings in Flatland, animate or inanimate, no matter what their form, present to our view the same, or nearly the same, appearance, viz. that of a straight Line. How then can one be distinguished from another, where all appear the same?

答案有三方面。首先，识别的手段是听觉；我们的听觉远比你们发达得多，它不仅使我们能够通过朋友的声音进行区分，甚至能够区分不同的阶级，至少就三个最低等级而言：等边形、正方形和五边形——至于等腰三角形，我不考虑。但随着社会地位的上升，通过听觉进行辨别和被辨别变得越来越困难，部分原因是声音被同化，部分原因是辨别声音的能力是平民的美德，在贵族阶层中并不发达。只要有任何冒充的危险，我们就不能依赖这种方法。在我们最低等级的人中，发音器官的发达程度远超听觉，因此等腰三角形可以轻松地模仿多边形的声音，经过一些训练，甚至可以模仿圆形的声音。因此，第二种方法更为普遍。

The answer is threefold. The first means of recognition is the sense of hearing; which with us is far more highly developed than with you, and which enables us not only to distinguish by the voice of our personal friends, but even to discriminate between different classes, at least so far as concerns the three lowest orders, the Equilateral, the Square, and the Pentagon—for of the Isosceles I take no account. But as we ascend in the social scale, the process of discriminating and being discriminated by hearing increases in difficulty, partly because voices are assimilated, partly because the faculty of voice-discrimination is a plebeian virtue not much developed among the Aristocracy. And wherever there is any danger of imposture we cannot trust to this method. Amongst our lowest orders, the vocal organs are developed to a degree more than correspondent with those of hearing, so that an Isosceles can easily feign the voice of a Polygon, and, with some training, that of a Circle himself. A second method is therefore more commonly resorted to.

在我们妇女和下层阶级中——至于上层阶级，我稍后会谈到——感觉是识别的主要标准，至少在陌生人之间是如此，尤其当问题不在于个人，而在于阶级时。因此，在太空国的上层阶级中，“介绍”的意义在于我们拥有“感觉”的过程。“请允许我请你感受我的朋友某某先生，并被他感受”——在远离城镇的那些较为保守的乡绅中，这仍然是平面国介绍的惯用套语。但在城镇和商人中，“被感受”一词会被省略，句子会被缩写为“请允许我请你感受我的朋友某某先生”；尽管当然，人们假设这种“感觉”是相互的。在我们更加现代、更加潇洒的年轻绅士们中——他们极其厌恶多余的努力，也极其不关心他们母语的纯洁性——这个套语被进一步限制，使用“感觉”一词作为专业意义，即“为了感觉和被感觉而推荐”；而此时，上流社会礼貌或快节奏的“俚语”认可了这样一种粗鲁的说法：“史密斯先生，请允许我触摸你，琼斯先生。”

Feeling is, among our Women and lower classes—about our upper classes I shall speak presently—the principal test of recognition, at all events between strangers, and when the question is, not as to the individual, but as to the class. What therefore “introduction” is among the higher classes in Spaceland, that the process of “feeling” is with us. “Permit me to ask you to feel and be felt by my friend Mr. So-and-so”—is still, among the more old-fashioned of our country gentlemen in districts remote from towns, the customary formula for a Flatland introduction. But in the towns, and among men of business, the words “be felt by” are omitted and the sentence is abbreviated to, “Let me ask you to feel Mr. So-and-so”; although it is assumed, of course, that the “feeling” is to be reciprocal. Among our still more modern and dashing young gentlemen—who are extremely averse to superfluous effort and supremely indifferent to the purity of their native language—the formula is still further curtailed by the use of “to feel” in a technical sense, meaning, “to recommend-for-the-purposes-of-feeling-and being-felt”; and at this moment the “slang” of polite or fast society in the upper classes sanctions such a barbarism as “Mr. Smith, permit me to feel you Mr. Jones.”

然而，我的读者，请不要以为我们和你们一样，都是在“感觉”上费力地摸索，也不要以为我们必须摸遍每个人的各个侧面，才能确定他属于哪个类别。从学校开始，并在日常生活中不断积累的长期练习和训练，使我们能够通过触觉立即辨别等边三角形、正方形和五边形的各个角；而且，我不用说，一个无脑的顶点锐角等腰三角形即使用最迟钝的触觉也能一目了然。因此，通常只需触摸一个人的单个角即可；一旦确定，我们就能判断出对方的阶级，除非他确实属于贵族的上层。在这种情况下，难度就大得多。即使是我们温特布里奇大学的一位文学硕士，也曾将十边形和十二边形混淆；而在这所著名大学内外，几乎没有一位理学博士能够迅速而毫不犹豫地判断出贵族成员是二十边形还是二十四边形。

Let not my Reader however suppose that “feeling” is with us the tedious process that it would be with you, or that we find it necessary to feel right round all the sides of every individual before we determine the class to which he belongs. Long practice and training, begun in the schools and continued in the experience of daily life, enable us to discriminate at once by the sense of touch, between the angles of an equal-sided Triangle, Square, and Pentagon; and I need not say that the brainless vertex of an acute-angled Isosceles is obvious to the dullest touch. It is therefore not necessary, as a rule, to do more than feel a single angle of any individual; and this, once ascertained, tells us the class of the person whom we are addressing, unless indeed he belongs to the higher sections of the nobility. There the difficulty is much greater. Even a Master of Arts in our University of Wentbridge has been known to confuse a ten-sided with a twelve-sided Polygon; and there is hardly a Doctor of Science in or out of that famous University who could pretend to decide promptly and unhesitatingly between a twenty-sided and a twenty-four sided member of the Aristocracy.

读者如果还记得我上面摘录的《妇女法典》中的相关内容，就会很容易地看出，通过接触进行介绍需要谨慎小心。否则，角度可能会对粗心的“触角者”造成无法弥补的伤害。为了“触角者”的安全，触角者必须保持静止。此前，人们已经知道，一次惊吓、一次不安地挪动位置，甚至一个剧烈的喷嚏，都会对粗心大意的人造成致命的后果，扼杀许多原本有望建立的友谊。尤其是在三角形的下层阶级中，尤其如此。他们的眼睛离顶点太远，几乎无法注意到在他们身躯末端发生的事情。此外，他们生性粗鲁，对高度组织化的多边形的微妙触碰毫不敏感。那么，如果一个不由自主的头部摆动就夺走了国家宝贵的生命，那又有什么奇怪的呢？

Those of my readers who recall the extracts I gave above from the Legislative code concerning Women, will readily perceive that the process of introduction by contact requires some care and discretion. Otherwise the angles might inflict on the unwary Feeler irreparable injury. It is essential for the safety of the Feeler that the Felt should stand perfectly still. A start, a fidgety shifting of the position, yes, even a violent sneeze, has been known before now to prove fatal to the incautious, and to nip in the bud many a promising friendship. Especially is this true among the lower classes of the Triangles. With them, the eye is situated so far from their vertex that they can scarcely take cognizance of what goes on at that extremity of their frame. They are moreover of a rough coarse nature, not sensitive to the delicate touch of the highly organized Polygon. What wonder then if an involuntary toss of the head has ere now deprived the State of a valuable life!

我听说我杰出的祖父——在他那不幸的等腰三角形阶级中，他是最不规则的，而且在他去世前不久，还获得了卫生与社会委员会七票中的四票，将他纳入等边三角形——他常常潸然泪下，痛惜他的高祖父也曾遭遇过类似的失败。他的高祖父是一位受人尊敬的工人，脑角或脑袋角是59°30'。据他所述，我那不幸的祖先患有风湿病，在被一个多边形触诊时，突然一惊，不小心把这位大人物从对角线上刺穿了；这一来，一方面是因为他长期被监禁和贬低，另一方面是因为我祖先所有亲属都受到了精神上的打击，导致我们家族在向美好生活迈进的道路上倒退了一步半。结果是，到了下一代，这个家族的大脑角度只记录在58°，直到五代之后才收复失地，达到完整的60°，最终实现了从等腰三角形上升。而这一系列的灾难，都源于感觉过程中的一个小小的意外。

I have heard that my excellent Grandfather—one of the least irregular of his unhappy Isosceles class, who indeed obtained, shortly before his decease, four out of seven votes from the Sanitary and Social Board for passing him into the class of the Equal-sided—often deplored, with a tear in his venerable eye, a miscarriage of this kind, which had occurred to his great-great-great-Grandfather, a respectable Working Man with an angle or brain of 59° 30’. According to his account, my unfortunate Ancestor, being afflicted with rheumatism, and in the act of being felt by a Polygon, by one sudden start accidentally transfixed the Great Man through the diagonal; and thereby, partly in consequence of his long imprisonment and degradation, and partly because of the moral shock which pervaded the whole of my Ancestor’s relations, threw back our family a degree and a half in their ascent towards better things. The result was that in the next generation the family brain was registered at only 58°, and not till the lapse of five generations was the lost ground recovered, the full 60° attained, and the Ascent from the Isosceles finally achieved. And all this series of calamities from one little accident in the process of Feeling.

说到这儿，我好像听到一些受过良好教育的读者惊呼：“你们这些平面国的人怎么会知道角度、度数或分呢？我们之所以能看到角度，是因为在太空中，我们能看到两条倾斜的直线。但是你每次只能看到一条直线，或者至少只能看到一条直线上的多条直线，你怎么能辨别任何角度，更不用说记录不同大小的角度了？”

At this point I think I hear some of my better educated readers exclaim, “How could you in Flatland know anything about angles and degrees, or minutes? We can see an angle, because we, in the region of Space, can see two straight lines inclined to one another; but you, who can see nothing but one straight line at a time, or at all events only a number of bits of straight lines all in one straight line,—how can you ever discern any angle, and much less register angles of different sizes?”

我的答案是，虽然我们看不见角度，但我们可以推断角度，而且推断得非常精确。我们因需要而生的触觉，经过长期训练而发展，使我们能够比视觉更准确地辨别角度，即使没有尺子或角度测量工具的帮助。我还必须解释一下，我们拥有强大的自然力量。我们的自然法则是，等腰三角形的大脑起始角度为半度，即三十分，并且每一代都会增加半度（如果它真的增加的话）；直到达到60°的目标，那时农奴制就结束了，自由民进入了正规军的行列。

I answer that though we cannot see angles, we can infer them, and this with great precision. Our sense of touch, stimulated by necessity, and developed by long training, enables us to distinguish angles far more accurately than your sense of sight, when unaided by a rule or measure of angles. Nor must I omit to explain that we have great natural helps. It is with us a Law of Nature that the brain of the Isosceles class shall begin at half a degree, or thirty minutes, and shall increase (if it increases at all) by half a degree in every generation; until the goal of 60° is reached, when the condition of serfdom is quitted, and the freeman enters the class of Regulars.

因此，大自然为我们提供了从半度到60度的递增角度等级或字母表，全国各地的小学都摆放着这些样本。由于偶尔出现的倒退，更常见的是道德和智力的停滞，以及罪犯和流浪汉阶层的异常繁衍，半度和单度阶层的个体总是过剩，而10度以下的样本也相当丰富。这些人完全没有公民权利；他们中的许多人甚至智力不足以应对战争，因此被各州送去从事教育工作。为了消除所有危险的可能性，他们被铐住无法移动，被安置在我们幼儿园的教室里，在那里，教育委员会利用他们来向中产阶级的后代传授这些可怜的家伙们自身完全缺乏的机智和智慧。

Consequently, Nature herself supplies us with an ascending scale or Alphabet of angles for half a degree up to 60°, specimens of which are placed in every Elementary School throughout the land. Owing to occasional retrogressions, to still more frequent moral and intellectual stagnation, and to the extraordinary fecundity of the Criminal and Vagabond Classes, there is always a vast superfluity of individuals of the half degree and single degree class, and a fair abundance of Specimens up to 10°. These are absolutely destitute of civil rights; and a great number of them, not having even intelligence enough for the purposes of warfare, are devoted by the States to the service of education. Fettered immovably so as to remove all possibility of danger, they are placed in the class rooms of our Infant Schools, and there they are utilized by the Board of Education for the purpose of imparting to the offspring of the Middle Classes that tact and intelligence of which these wretched creatures themselves are utterly devoid.

在一些州，样本偶尔会得到食物，并允许其生存数年；但在气候更温和、管理更完善的地区，从长远来看，为了年轻人的教育利益，更有利的做法是省去食物，每月给样本换新——这大约相当于罪犯阶层不吃东西的平均生存时间。在成本较低的学校，样本生存时间延长所带来的好处，一部分是食物支出，一部分是角度精度的下降，因为经过几周的持续“感知”，角度精度就会下降。在列举更昂贵系统的优势时，我们也不应忘记补充一点，它有助于减少多余的等腰三角形人口，尽管这种减少幅度很小，但却是显而易见的——这是平面国每位政治家始终关注的目标。因此，总体而言——尽管我并非不知道，在许多民选的学校董事会中，存在着对所谓“廉价制度”的支持——但我本人倾向于认为，这是众多以开支为最真正经济的案例之一。

In some states the Specimens are occasionally fed and suffered to exist for several years; but in the more temperate and better regulated regions, it is found in the long run more advantageous for the educational interests of the young, to dispense with food, and to renew the Specimens every month,—which is about the average duration of the foodless existence of the Criminal class. In the cheaper schools, what is gained by the longer existence of the Specimens is lost, partly in the expenditure for food, and partly in the diminished accuracy of the angles, which are impaired after a few weeks of constant “feeling.” Nor must we forget to add, in enumerating the advantages of the more expensive system, that it tends, though slightly yet perceptibly, to the diminution of the redundant Isosceles population—an object which every statesman in Flatland constantly keeps in view. On the whole therefore—although I am not ignorant that, in many popularly elected School Boards, there is a reaction in favour of “the cheap system,” as it is called—I am myself disposed to think that this is one of the many cases in which expense is the truest economy.

但我不能让学校董事会的政治问题分散我的注意力主题。我相信，以上所述足以表明，通过感觉识别并非像人们想象的那样冗长乏味或难以抉择；而且它显然比通过听觉识别更可靠。然而，正如上文所指出的，仍然存在反对意见，认为这种方法并非没有风险。因此，许多中下阶层人士，以及多边形和圆形修会的所有人，都倾向于第三种方法，对此的描述将留到下一节。

But I must not allow questions of School Board politics to divert me from my subject. Enough has been said, I trust, to shew that Recognition by Feeling is not so tedious or indecisive a process as might have been supposed; and it is obviously more trustworthy than Recognition by hearing. Still there remains, as has been pointed out above, the objection that this method is not without danger. For this reason many in the Middle and Lower classes, and all without exception in the Polygonal and Circular orders, prefer a third method, the description of which shall be reserved for the next section.

§6：论视觉识别

§ 6: Of Recognition by Sight

我接下来要显得前后矛盾了。在前面几节中，我说过平面国的所有图形都呈现出一条直线；并且还加上或暗示了，因此视觉器官无法区分不同种类的个体：但现在我要向那些批评空间国的人解释，我们是如何通过视觉来相互识别的。

I am about to appear very inconsistent. In the previous sections I have said that all figures in Flatland present the appearance of a straight line; and it was added or implied, that it is consequently impossible to distinguish by the visual organ between individuals of different classes: yet now I am about to explain to my Spaceland critics how we are able to recognize one another by the sense of sight.

然而，如果读者愿意费心去查阅那段论述感觉识别具有普遍性的段落，他就会发现这个限定条件——“在下层阶级中”。只有在上层阶级和我们较为温和的气候条件下，视觉识别才会被实践。

If however the Reader will take the trouble to refer to the passage in which Recognition by Feeling is stated to be universal, he will find this qualification—“among the lower classes.” It is only among the higher classes and in our more temperate climates that Sight Recognition is practised.

这种力量存在于任何地区、任何阶层，都是雾的结果；除热带地区外，一年中大部分时间，雾都普遍存在。在太空国度，雾是一种纯粹的邪恶，遮蔽了景色，令人精神萎靡，损害了健康。而我们却认为雾是几乎不逊于空气的恩赐，是艺术的哺育者，科学的养育者。让我解释一下我的意思，不再对这种恩惠赞颂。

That this power exists in any regions and for any classes, is the result of Fog; which prevails during the greater part of the year in all parts save the torrid zones. That which is with you in Spaceland an unmixed evil, blotting out the landscape, depressing the spirits, and enfeebling the health, is by us recognized as a blessing scarcely inferior to air itself, and as the Nurse of arts and Parent of sciences. But let me explain my meaning, without further eulogies on this beneficent Element.

如果没有雾，所有线条都会显得同样清晰，难以辨别；事实上，在那些气候干燥透明的贫困地区，情况确实如此。但是，在雾气弥漫的地方，距离物体（比如说三英尺）会比距离物体（两英尺十一英寸）明显暗淡；因此，通过仔细、持续地进行相对明暗度的实验观察，我们能够非常准确地推断出所观察物体的形状。

If Fog were non-existent, all lines would appear equally and indistinguishably clear; and this is actually the case in those unhappy countries in which the atmosphere is perfectly dry and transparent. But wherever there is a rich supply of Fog, objects that are at a distance, say of three feet, are appreciably dimmer than those at a distance of two feet eleven inches; and the result is that by careful and constant experimental observation of comparative dimness and clearness, we are enabled to infer with great exactness the configuration of the object observed.

一个实例比大量的概括更能清楚地表达我的意思。

An instance will do more than a volume of generalities to make my meaning clear.

假设我看到两个人走过来，我想确定他们的等级。我们假设他们分别是商人和医生，或者换句话说，一个等边三角形和一个五边形：我该如何区分他们呢？

Suppose I see two individuals approaching whose rank I wish to ascertain. They are, we will suppose, a Merchant and a Physician, or in other words, an Equilateral Triangle and a Pentagon: how am I to distinguish them?

对于每个接触过几何学研​​究门槛的太空世界的孩子来说，如果我能用眼睛看到一个角，（A）对于正在走近的陌生人，我的视线将均匀地位于他靠近我的两侧（即CA和AB）之间，这样我就可以公正地看待这两个人，并且两者看起来大小相同。

It will be obvious, to every child in Spaceland who has touched the threshold of Geometrical Studies, that, if I can bring my eye so that its glance may bisect an angle (A) of the approaching stranger, my view will lie as it were evenly between his two sides that are next to me (viz. CA and AB), so that I shall contemplate the two impartially, and both will appear of the same size.

现在，就商人（ I ）的情况而言，我会看到什么？我会看到一条直线DAE，其中间点（A）会非常明亮，因为它离我最近；但这条线的两边会迅速变暗，因为边AC和AB 会迅速消失在雾中；而在我看来，商人的两端，即D和E，会非常暗淡。

Now in the case of (I) the Merchant, what shall I see? I shall see a straight line DAE, in which the middle point (A) will be very bright because it is nearest to me; but on either side the line will shade away rapidly into dimness, because sides AC and AB recede rapidly into the fog; and what appear to me as the Merchant’s extremities, viz. D and E, will be very dim indeed.

另一方面，在 (2) 医生的案例中，虽然我在这里也能看到一条线 ( D' A'E ' ) ，其中心 ( A ') 很明亮，但它逐渐变暗的速度会慢一些，因为两侧 ( A'C ' 、A'B ' )逐渐消退到雾中的速度会慢一些；而且在我看来，医生的两端，即D '和E '，不会像商人的两端那样暗淡。

On the other hand in the case of (2) the Physician, though I shall here also see a line (D´A´E´) with a bright centre (A´), yet it will shade away less rapidly into dimness, because the sides (A´C´, A´B´) recede less rapidly into the fog; and what appear to me the Physician’s extremities, viz. D´ and E´, will be not so dim as the extremities of the Merchant.

读者或许能从这两个例子中理解，经过长期训练并不断积累经验，我们当中受过良好教育的阶层能够凭借视觉相当准确地区分中等和最低等的个体。如果我的“太空国度”赞助人能够理解这一基本概念，认识到这种可能性，并且不将我的解释视为完全不可信而予以拒绝，那么我就达到了我所能合理期待的一切。如果我进一步阐述细节，只会令人困惑。然而，对于那些年轻且缺乏经验的人来说，他们或许会从我上面给出的两个简单例子中推断出我如何认出我的父亲和儿子，认为通过视觉识别是一件轻而易举的事情，因此有必要指出，在现实生活中，视觉识别的大多数问题要微妙和复杂得多。

The Reader will probably understand from these two instances how—after a very long training supplemented by constant experience—it is possible for the well-educated classes among us to discriminate with fair accuracy between the middle and lowest orders, by the sense of sight. If my Spaceland Patrons have grasped this general conception, so far as to conceive the possibility of it and not to reject my account as altogether incredible—I shall have attained all I can reasonably expect. Were I to attempt further details I should only perplex. Yet for the sake of the young and inexperienced, who may perchance infer—from the two simple instances I have given above, of the manner in which I should recognize my Father and my Sons—that Recognition by sight is an easy affair, it may be needful to point out that in actual life most of the problems of Sight Recognition are far more subtle and complex.

例如，当我的父亲，那个三角形，走近我时，他恰好向我展示的是他的边而不是角，那么，在我要求他旋转，或者在我把目光移到他身上之前，我暂时会怀疑他是不是一条直线，或者换句话说，一个女人。还有，当我和我的两个六边形孙子中的一个在一起，凝视着他的一条边（AB）的正面时，从附图中可以明显看出，我会看到一条完整的线（AB）具有相对的亮度（末端几乎没有阴影），而两条较小的线（CA和BD ）始终暗淡，并且朝向末端C和D逐渐变暗。

If for example, when my Father, the Triangle, approaches me, he happens to present his side to me instead of his angle, then, until I have asked him to rotate, or until I have edged my eye around him, I am for the moment doubtful whether he may not be a Straight Line, or, in other words, a Woman. Again, when I am in the company of one of my two hexagonal Grandsons, contemplating one of his sides (AB) full front, it will be evident from the accompanying diagram that I shall see one whole line (AB) in comparative brightness (shading off hardly at all at the ends) and two smaller lines (CA and BD) dim throughout and shading away into greater dimness toward the extremities C and D.

但我绝不能屈服于扩大这些话题的诱惑。即使是太空国里最卑微的数学家也会轻易相信我，当我断言，生活中的问题，呈现在受过良好教育的人面前——当他们自身处于运动状态，旋转、前进或后退，同时试图通过视觉区分许多朝不同方向移动的高级多边形时，例如在舞厅或会客室——必定具有考验最聪明的人的棱角的性质，并充分证明了著名的温特布里奇大学静态和动态几何学博学教授的丰厚天赋，在那里，视觉识别的科学和艺术定期向美国各界精英传授。

But I must not give way to the temptation of enlarging on these topics. The meanest mathematician in Spaceland will readily believe me when I assert that the problems of life, which present themselves to the well-educated—when they are themselves in motion, rotating, advancing or retreating, and at the same time attempting to discriminate by the sense of sight between a number of Polygons of high rank moving in different directions, as for example in a ball-room or conversazione—must be of a nature to task the angularity of the most intellectual, and amply justify the rich endowments of the Learned Professors of Geometry, both Static and Kinetic, in the illustrious University of Wentbridge, where the Science and Art of Sight Recognition are regularly taught to large classes of the élite of the States.

只有我们最显赫、最富有的家族子弟中，少数人才能拿出必要的时间和金钱，彻底推行这项高贵而宝贵的艺术。即便对我这样一个出身显赫的数学家，以及两个最有希望、最完美的正六边形的祖父来说，置身于一群上流社会旋转的多边形之中，有时也会感到十分困惑。当然，对于一个普通的商人或农奴来说，这样的景象几乎和你，我的读者，突然来到我们国家一样难以理解。

It is only a few of the scions of our noblest and wealthiest houses, who are able to give the time and money necessary for the thorough prosecution of this noble and valuable Art. Even to me, a Mathematician of no mean standing, and the Grandfather of two most hopeful and perfectly regular Hexagons, to find myself in the midst of a crowd of rotating Polygons of the higher classes, is occasionally very perplexing. And of course to a common Tradesman, or Serf, such a sight is almost as unintelligible as it would be to you, my Reader, were you suddenly transported into our country.

在这样的人群中，你周围只能看到一条线，看似笔直，但其各部分明暗不规则地不断变化。即使你已经完成了大学三年级的五边形和六边形课程，并且精通这门学科的理论，你仍然会发现，你需要多年的经验积累，才能在上流社会中不与比你高的人推挤。要求他们“感受”是有违礼仪的，他们凭借优越的文化和教养，对你的一举一动了如指掌，而你对他们的一举一动却知之甚少，甚至一无所知。总而言之，要想在多边形社会中举止得体，一个人自己就应该成为一个多边形。至少这是我痛苦的经历给我的教训。

In such a crowd you could see on all sides of you nothing but a Line, apparently straight, but of which the parts would vary irregularly and perpetually in brightness or dimness. Even if you had completed your third year in the Pentagonal and Hexagonal classes in the University, and were perfect in the theory of the subject, you would still find that there was need of many years of experience, before you could move in a fashionable crowd without jostling against your betters, whom it is against etiquette to ask to “feel,” and who, by their superior culture and breeding, know all about your movements, while you know very little or nothing about theirs. In a word, to comport oneself with perfect propriety in Polygonal society, one ought to be a Polygon oneself. Such at least is the painful teaching of my experience.

令人惊奇的是，视觉识别的艺术——或者我几乎可以称之为本能——很大程度上是通过习惯性练习和回避“感觉”的习惯而发展起来的。就像你们这些聋哑人，即使允许他们打手势和使用手写字母，也永远无法掌握更难掌握但更有价值的唇语和唇读技巧一样，我们对于“看”和“感觉”也是如此。早年依赖“感觉”的人，永远无法完美地掌握“看”。

It is astonishing how much the Art—or I may almost call it instinct—of Sight Recognition is developed by the habitual practice of it and by the avoidance of the custom of “Feeling.” Just as, with you, the deaf and dumb, if once allowed to gesticulate and to use the hand-alphabet, will never acquire the more difficult but far more valuable art of lip-speech and lip-reading, so it is with us as regards “Seeing” and “Feeling.” None who in early life resort to “Feeling” will ever learn “Seeing” in perfection.

因此，在我们的高年级学生中，“情感”是被劝阻或绝对禁止的。他们的孩子从摇篮起就被送往专门的高等神学院，而不是去公立小学（在那里教授情感的艺术）；在我们杰出的大学里，“情感”被视为极其严重的错误，初犯会被开除学籍，再犯则会被开除学籍。

For this reason, among our Higher Classes, “Feeling” is discouraged or absolutely forbidden. From the cradle their children, instead of going to the Public Elementary schools (where the art of Feeling is taught,) are sent to higher Seminaries of an exclusive character; and at our illustrious University, to “feel” is regarded as a most serious fault, involving Rustication for the first offence, and Expulsion for the second.

但在下层阶级，视觉识别的技艺被视为遥不可及的奢侈品。普通的商人根本无法承担儿子一生三分之一的时间投入抽象研究的重担。因此，贫困家庭的孩子从小就被允许“感受”，从而获得了早熟和早期的活力，这与多边形阶级那些半吊子青年的迟钝、不成熟和无精打采形成了鲜明对比；但当后者最终完成大学学业，准备将理论付诸实践时，他们身上发生的变化几乎可以被描述为一次新生，在每一项艺术、科学和社会事业中，他们都迅速赶超并远远甩开三角形阶级的竞争对手。

But among the lower classes the art of Sight Recognition is regarded as an unattainable luxury. A common Tradesman cannot afford to let his son spend a third of his life in abstract studies. The children of the poor are therefore allowed to “feel” from their earliest years, and they gain thereby a precocity and an early vivacity which contrast at first most favourably with the inert, undeveloped, and listless behaviour of the half-instructed youths of the Polygonal class; but when the latter have at last completed their University course, and are prepared to put their theory into practice, the change that comes over them may almost be described as a new birth, and in every art, science, and social pursuit they rapidly overtake and distance their Triangular competitors.

只有少数多边形阶级未能通过大学期末考试或毕业考试。这少数未能成功者的情况实在令人悲哀。他们既被上流社会拒之门外，又被下流社会鄙视。他们既缺乏多边形阶级学士和硕士那种成熟且经过系统训练的能力，又缺乏年轻商人那种与生俱来的早熟和多才多艺。各种职业，包括公共服务，都对他们不开放；尽管在大多数州，他们实际上并没有被禁止结婚，但他们在建立合适的婚姻方面却极其困难，因为经验表明，这种不幸且天赋不佳的父母所生的孩子，即使不是完全不合格的，通常也是不幸的。

Only a few of the Polygonal Class fail to pass the Final Test or Leaving Examination at the University. The condition of the unsuccessful minority is truly pitiable. Rejected from the higher class, they are also despised by the lower. They have neither the matured and systematically trained powers of the Polygonal Bachelors and Masters of Arts, nor yet the native precocity and mercurial versatility of the youthful Tradesman. The professions, the public services, are closed against them; and though in most States they are not actually debarred from marriage, yet they have the greatest difficulty in forming suitable alliances, as experience shows that the offspring of such unfortunate and ill-endowed parents is generally itself unfortunate, if not positively Irregular.

过去各个时代发生的大骚乱和叛乱，一般都是从这些我们贵族的废物中衍生出领导者的；由此产生的危害是如此之大，以至于我们越来越少数的进步政治家认为，真正的仁慈将决定彻底镇压这些骚乱，通过颁布法令，那些没有通过大学期末考试的人要么被终身监禁，要么被无痛苦地处死。

It is from these specimens of the refuse of our Nobility that the great Tumults and Seditions of past ages have generally derived their leaders; and so great is the mischief thence arising that an increasing minority of our more progressive Statesmen are of opinion that true mercy would dictate their entire suppression, by enacting that all who fail to pass the Final Examination of the University should be either imprisoned for life, or extinguished by a painless death.

但我发现自己已经跑题讨论“违规行为”这个话题了，这个问题至关重要，需要用单独的章节来讨论。

But I find myself digressing into the subject of Irregularities, a matter of such vital interest that it demands a separate section.

§7：关于不规则图形

§ 7: Concerning Irregular Figures

在前面的篇幅中，我一直在假设——或许一开始就应该作为一个独特而基本的命题提出——平面国的每个人都是规则图形，也就是说，具有规则的结构。我的意思是，女人不仅必须是一条线，而且必须是一条直线；工匠或士兵的两条边必须相等；商人的三条边必须相等；律师（我属于这一类，但并不出名）的四条边必须相等；而且，一般来说，每个多边形的所有边都必须相等。

Throughout the previous pages I have been assuming—what perhaps should have been laid down at the beginning as a distinct and fundamental proposition—that every human being in Flatland is a Regular Figure, that is to say of regular construction. By this I mean that a Woman must not only be a line, but a straight line; that an Artisan or Soldier must have two of his sides equal; that Tradesmen must have three sides equal; Lawyers (of which class I am a humble member), four sides equal, and, generally, that in every Polygon, all the sides must be equal.

边长当然取决于个体的年龄。女性出生时身长约为一英寸，而身材高大的成年女性则可能长达一英尺。至于各个阶层的男性，粗略地说，成年人的边长加起来大约是两英尺或略长一些。但我们这里不讨论边长。我指的是边长相等，不需过多思考就能看出，平面国的整个社会生活都建立在一个基本事实之上：大自然希望所有图形的边长相等。

The sizes of the sides would of course depend upon the age of the individual. A Female at birth would be about an inch long, while a tall adult Woman might extend to a foot. As to the Males of every class, it may be roughly said that the length of an adult’s sides, when added together, is two feet or a little more. But the size of our sides is not under consideration. I am speaking of the equality of sides, and it does not need much reflection to see that the whole of the social life in Flatland rests upon the fundamental fact that Nature wills all Figures to have their sides equal.

如果我们的边不等，我们的角度也可能不等。仅仅通过感觉或视觉估计一个角度不足以确定一个人的体型，就必须通过感觉实验来确定每个角度。但人生苦短，不值得进行如此乏味的摸索。视觉识别的整个科学和艺术将立即消亡；感觉，就其本身而言，是一门艺术，将无法长久存在；交往将变得危险或不可能；所有的信任和深谋远虑都将不复存在；没有人能够安全地进行最简单的社交安排；总之，文明可能会重新陷入野蛮。

If our sides were unequal our angles might be unequal. Instead of its being sufficient to feel, or estimate by sight, a single angle in order to determine the form of an individual, it would be necessary to ascertain each angle by the experiment of Feeling. But life would be too short for such a tedious groping. The whole science and art of Sight Recognition would at once perish; Feeling, so far as it is an art, would not long survive; intercourse would become perilous or impossible; there would be an end to all confidence, all forethought; no one would be safe in making the most simple social arrangements; in a word, civilization might relapse into barbarism.

我是不是太快就让读者得出这些显而易见的结论了？只需片刻的思考，加上日常生活中的一个小例子，就能让每个人都相信，我们整个社会体系都建立在规则性或角相等的基础上。比如，你在街上遇到两三个商人，你一眼就能看出他们的角度和快速变暗的边，于是就邀请他们到你家吃午饭。你现在非常自信地这么做了，因为每个人都知道一个成年三角形所占的面积精确到一两英寸：但想象一下，你家的商人拖着他的规则和可观的顶点，对角线为十二或十三英寸的平行四边形： - 你要拿这样一个怪物怎么办呢？它牢牢地卡在你家的门上？

Am I going too fast to carry my Readers with me to these obvious conclusions? Surely a moment’s reflection, and a single instance from common life, must convince every one that our whole social system is based upon Regularity, or Equality of Angles. You meet, for example, two or three Tradesmen in the street, whom you recognize at once to be Tradesmen by a glance at their angles and rapidly bedimmed sides, and you ask them to step into your house to lunch. This you do at present with perfect confidence, because everyone knows to an inch or two the area occupied by an adult Triangle: but imagine that your Tradesman drags behind his regular and respectable vertex, a parallelogram of twelve or thirteen inches in diagonal:—what are you to do with such a monster sticking fast in your house door?

但我列举的细节，对每个在太空国居住的人而言，都是显而易见的，这无疑是在侮辱读者的智商。显然，在如此不祥的情况下，仅仅测量一个角度已经不够了；一个人的一生都将用于感知或勘察熟人的周长。在人群中避免碰撞的困难，已经足以考验即使是一个受过良好教育的正方形的智慧；但如果没有人能计算出人群中某个人影的规则性，那么一切都会变得混乱不堪，哪怕是最轻微的恐慌都可能造成严重的伤害，或者——如果碰巧有妇女或士兵在场——甚至可能造成重大的生命损失。

But I am insulting the intelligence of my Readers by accumulating details which must be patent to everyone who enjoys the advantages of a Residence in Spaceland. Obviously the measurements of a single angle would no longer be sufficient under such portentous circumstances; one’s whole life would be taken up in feeling or surveying the perimeter of one’s acquaintances. Already the difficulties of avoiding a collision in a crowd are enough to tax the sagacity of even a well-educated Square; but if no one could calculate the Regularity of a single figure in the company, all would be chaos and confusion, and the slightest panic would cause serious injuries, or—if there happened to be any Women or Soldiers present—perhaps considerable loss of life.

因此，权宜之计与自然界一致，认可了几何构形的规则性：法律也毫不犹豫地支持了他们的努力。“图形不规则性”在我们这里的含义，与你们这里的含义相同，甚至更甚，是道德偏差与犯罪行为的结合，因此也应如此处理。诚然，不乏一些悖论的传播者，他们坚持认为几何不规则性和道德不规则性之间没有必然联系。他们说：“不规范行为人从出生起就被父母鄙视，被兄弟姐妹嘲笑，被佣人冷落，被社会鄙视和怀疑，被排除在一切责任重大、值得信赖和有益活动的岗位之外。他的一举一动都受到警方的严密监视，直到他成年接受检查；如果发现他超出了规定的偏差范围，要么被处决，要么被关进政府办公室，成为七等文员；被禁止结婚；被迫从事一份乏味的工作，领取微薄的薪水；不得不在办公室里吃住，甚至休假也要受到严密的监视；难怪即使是最善良、最纯洁的人性，也会在这样的环境中变得痛苦和扭曲！”

Expediency therefore concurs with Nature in stamping the seal of its approval upon Regularity of conformation: nor has the Law been backward in seconding their efforts. “Irregularity of Figure” means with us the same as, or more than, a combination of moral obliquity and criminality with you, and is treated accordingly. There are not wanting, it is true, some promulgators of paradoxes who maintain that there is no necessary connection between geometrical and moral Irregularity. “The Irregular,” they say, “is from his birth scouted by his own parents, derided by his brothers and sisters, neglected by the domestics, scorned and suspected by society, and excluded from all posts of responsibility, trust, and useful activity. His every movement is jealously watched by the police till he comes of age and presents himself for inspection; then he is either destroyed, if he is found to exceed the fixed margin of deviation, or else immured in a Government Office as a clerk of the seventh class; prevented from marriage; forced to drudge at an uninteresting occupation for a miserable stipend; obliged to live and board at the office, and to take even his vacation under close supervision; what wonder that human nature, even in the best and purest, is embittered and perverted by such surroundings!”

所有这些看似合理的推理，并不能说服我，就像它也无法说服我们最睿智的政治家一样，我们的祖先错误地将容忍不规则行为与国家安全不相容定为一项政策公理。毫无疑问，不规则人员的生活很艰苦；但大多数人的利益要求他们的生活必须艰苦。如果允许一个前胸三角形、后背多边形的人生存下去，并繁衍出更加不规则的后代，那么人生的艺术将会变成什么样？难道平面国的房屋、门和教堂都要改造，以容纳这样的怪物吗？难道我们的检票员在允许每个人进入剧院或在演讲厅就座之前，都要测量他的周长吗？难道不规则人员可以免除民兵的义务吗？如果不能，如何才能防止他把毁灭带入他的同伴队伍？再说，这种人必然会面临难以抗拒的欺诈诱惑！他可以轻而易举地走进一家商店，向一个值得信赖的商人订购任何数量的货物！让那些虚伪的慈善家们为废除不规则刑法辩护吧，就我而言，我从未见过一个不规则者不是造物主显然希望他成为的样子——一个伪君子、一个厌世者，并且，在他的权力范围内——一个各种恶作剧的制造者。

All this very plausible reasoning does not convince me, as it has not convinced the wisest of our Statesmen, that our ancestors erred in laying it down as an axiom of policy that the toleration of Irregularity is incompatible with the safety of the State. Doubtless, the life of an Irregular is hard; but the interests of the Greater Number require that it shall be hard. If a man with a triangular front and a polygonal back were allowed to exist and to propagate a still more Irregular posterity, what would become of the arts of life? Are the houses and doors and churches in Flatland to be altered in order to accommodate such monsters? Are our ticket-collectors to be required to measure every man’s perimeter before they allow him to enter a theatre, or to take his place in a lecture room? Is an Irregular to be exempted from the militia? And if not, how is he to be prevented from carrying desolation into the ranks of his comrades? Again, what irresistible temptations to fraudulent impostures must needs beset such a creature! How easy for him to enter a shop with his polygonal front foremost, and to order goods to any extent from a confiding Tradesman! Let the advocates of a falsely called Philanthropy plead as they may for the abrogation of the Irregular Penal Laws, I for my part have never known an Irregular who was not also what Nature evidently intended him to be—a hypocrite, a misanthropist, and, up to the limits of his power—a perpetrator of all manner of mischief.

我并非倾向于（目前）推荐某些州采取的极端措施，即婴儿的出生角度若偏离正常角度半度，即被立即处死。我们一些最杰出、最有能力、真正天才的人物，在他们幼年时期，曾承受着长达四十五分钟甚至更久的畸形：而他们宝贵生命的逝去，对国家而言将是无法弥补的损失。医疗技术在压迫、伸展、环钻、绑扎以及其他外科或营养手术方面也取得了一些最辉煌的成就，通过这些手术，畸形得到了部分或全部治愈。因此，我提倡“中间道路”（Via Media），不会设定任何固定或绝对的界限；但在婴儿骨骼刚刚开始发育，且医疗委员会报告无法康复的时期，我建议对畸形婴儿进行无痛且仁慈的处死。

Not that I should be disposed to recommend (at present) the extreme measures adopted in some States, where an infant whose angle deviates by half a degree from the correct angularity is summarily destroyed at birth. Some of our highest and ablest men, men of real genius, have during their earliest days laboured under deviations as great as, or even greater than, forty-five minutes: and the loss of their precious lives would have been an irreparable injury to the State. The art of healing also has achieved some of its most glorious triumphs in the compressions, extensions, trepannings, colligations, and other surgical or diaetetic operations by which Irregularity has been partly or wholly cured. Advocating, therefore a Via Media, I would lay down no fixed or absolute line of demarcation; but at the period when the frame is just beginning to set, and when the Medical Board has reported that recovery is improbable, I would suggest that the Irregular offspring be painlessly and mercifully consumed.

§8：古代绘画实践

§ 8: Of the Ancient Practice of Painting

如果我的读者一直关​​注到这里，听到平面国的生活有些乏味，他们就不会感到惊讶。当然，我的意思并非说没有战争、阴谋、骚乱、派系斗争，以及所有那些据说能让历史变得有趣的现象；我也不否认，生活问题和数学问题的奇特融合，不断地引发猜测，也提供了立即验证的机会，赋予了我们生存一种你们在空间国难以理解的热情。我现在是从美学和艺术的角度来说的，我说我们的生活很乏味；从美学和艺术的角度来说，确实非常乏味。

If my Readers have followed me with any attention up to this point, they will not be surprised to hear that life is somewhat dull in Flatland. I do not, of course, mean that there are not battles, conspiracies, tumults, factions, and all those other phenomena which are supposed to make History interesting; nor would I deny that the strange mixture of the problems of life and the problems of Mathematics, continually inducing conjecture and giving the opportunity of immediate verification, imparts to our existence a zest which you in Spaceland can hardly comprehend. I speak now from the aesthetic and artistic point of view when I say that life with us is dull; aesthetically and artistically, very dull indeed.

如果一个人的所有前景、所有风景、历史作品、肖像、花卉、静物都只是一条线，除了明暗程度不同之外没有任何变化，那又怎么可能不是这样呢？

How can it be otherwise, when all one’s prospect, all one’s landscapes, historical pieces, portraits, flowers, still life, are nothing but a single line, with no varieties except degrees of brightness and obscurity?

事情并非总是如此。如果传统说得没错，色彩曾经在长达六个世纪甚至更久的时间里，为我们远古祖先的生活增添了一抹短暂的光彩。某个私人——一个五角大楼，名字各不相同据说，他偶然发现了一些简单色彩的构成要素和一种基本的绘画方法，首先开始装饰自己的房子，然后是奴隶，接着是父亲、儿子和孙子，最后是自己。其效果的便捷性和美观性都得到了所有人的称赞。无论色画家——最可靠的权威人士都一致这么称呼他——将他那色彩斑斓的身躯转向何处，都能立刻引起人们的注意和敬畏。现在，无需“触摸”他；无需将他的正面误认为背面；他的一举一动都能被邻人轻易地辨认出来，无需费力计算；无需推挤他，也无需为他让路；他的声音也省去了我们这些没有色彩的正方形和五边形在一群无知的等腰三角形中间穿梭时，常常被迫用那种费力的语气来彰显个性。

It was not always thus. Colour, if Tradition speaks the truth, once for the space of half a dozen centuries or more, threw a transient splendour over the lives of our ancestors in remote ages. Some private individual—a Pentagon whose name is variously reported—having casually discovered the constituents of the simpler colours and a rudimentary method of painting, is said to have begun by decorating first his house, then his slaves, then his Father, his Sons and Grandsons, lastly himself. The convenience as well as the beauty of the results commended themselves to all. Wherever Chromatistes,—for by that name the most trustworthy authorities concur in calling him,—turned his variegated frame, there he at once excited attention, and attracted respect. No one now needed to “feel” him; no one mistook his front for his back; all his movements were readily ascertained by his neighbours without the slightest strain on their powers of calculation; no one jostled him, or failed to make way for him; his voice was saved the labour of that exhausting utterance by which we colourless Squares and Pentagons are often forced to proclaim our individuality when we move amid a crowd of ignorant Isosceles.

这股风潮迅速蔓延。不到一周，该地区所有的正方形和三角形都纷纷效仿了色阶派的风格，只有少数较为保守的五边形仍然坚持着。一两个月后，就连十二边形也受到了这种新潮的影响。不到一年，除了最高级的贵族之外，几乎所有人都染上了这种颜色。毋庸置疑，这种习俗很快就从色阶派的地区传到了周边地区；两代之内，整个平面国除了妇女和祭司之外，已经没有人不穿肤色了。

The fashion spread like wildfire. Before a week was over, every Square and Triangle in the district had copied the example of Chromatistes, and only a few of the more conservative Pentagons still held out. A month or two found even the Dodecagons infected with the innovation. A year had not elapsed before the habit had spread to all but the very highest of the Nobility. Needless to say, the custom soon made its way from the district of Chromatistes to surrounding regions; and within two generations no one in all Flatland was colourless except the Women and the Priests.

大自然似乎在这里竖起了一道屏障，阻止创新扩展到这两类人。多面性几乎成了创新者​​们必不可少的借口。“自然界中，边的区分意味着颜色的区分”——这种诡辩在当时口口相传，一下子就让整座城镇的人皈依了新的文化。但这句格言显然不适用于我们的牧师和妇女。后者只有一条边，因此——从复数和学究式的角度来说——没有边。前者——至少如果他们愿意宣称自己是真正的圆形，而不是仅仅拥有无限多条无限小边的高级多边形的话——习惯于吹嘘（妇女们对此坦白并表示遗憾），它们也没有边，因为幸运地拥有一条线的周长，或者换句话说，一个圆周。因此，这两个阶层无法理解所谓的“区分侧面意味着区分颜色”这一公理；当所有其他人都屈服于肉体装饰的魅力时，只有牧师和妇女仍然保持着纯洁，没有受到油漆的污染。

Here Nature herself appeared to erect a barrier, and to plead against extending the innovations to these two classes. Many-sidedness was almost essential as a pretext for the Innovators. “Distinction of sides is intended by Nature to imply distinction of colours”—such was the sophism which in those days flew from mouth to mouth, converting whole towns at a time to the new culture. But manifestly to our Priests and Women this adage did not apply. The latter had only one side, and therefore—plurally and pedantically speaking—no sides. The former—if at least they would assert their claim to be really and truly Circles, and not mere high-class Polygons with an infinitely large number of infinitesimally small sides—were in the habit of boasting (what Women confessed and deplored) that they also had no sides, being blessed with a perimeter of one line or, in other words, a Circumference. Hence it came to pass that these two Classes could see no force in the so-called axiom about “Distinction of Sides implying Distinction of Colour”; and when all others had succumbed to the fascinations of corporal decoration, the Priests and the Women alone still remained pure from the pollution of paint.

不道德、放荡、无政府、不科学——随便你怎么称呼它们——然而，从美学角度来看，色彩革命的那些古老岁月，正是平面国艺术的光辉童年——可惜，这童年从未成长为男子汉，甚至没有达到青春的绽放。那时，活着本身就是一种喜悦，因为生活意味着观看。即使是小型聚会，观看人群也是一种享受；据说，教堂或剧院里丰富多彩的聚会，曾不止一次地分散了我们最伟大的教师和演员的注意力；但据说，最令人陶醉的，是军事检阅的无比壮丽。

Immoral, licentious, anarchical, unscientific—call them by what names you will—yet, from an aesthetic point of view, those ancient days of the Colour Revolt were the glorious childhood of Art in Flatland—a childhood, alas, that never ripened into manhood, nor even reached the blossom of youth. To live was then in itself a delight, because living implied seeing. Even at a small party, the company was a pleasure to behold; the richly varied hues of the assembly in a church or theatre are said to have more than once proved too distracting from our greatest teachers and actors; but most ravishing of all is said to have been the unspeakable magnificence of a military review.

两万名等腰三角形阵型的战线突然转向，将底边的暗黑色换成包括锐角在内的两边的橙色和紫色；等边三角形的民兵身着红、白、蓝三色制服；方形炮兵身着淡紫色、群青色、藤黄色和焦赭色制服，在朱红色大炮附近快速旋转；五色和六色的五边形和六边形在战场上飞驰而过，身穿外科医生、几何学家和副官的办公室——所有这一切足以让人相信那个著名的故事：一位杰出的圆人被他麾下军队的艺术之美所征服，扔掉了元帅权杖和王冠，惊呼从此以后他要把它们换成艺术家的铅笔。当时的语言和词汇本身就一定预示着当时感官发展有多么伟大和辉煌。颜色革命时期，最普通的市民最普通的言语，似乎都浸润着更丰富的词汇或思想；我们至今仍能从那个时代汲取最精妙的诗歌，以及那些在现代更科学的语言中依然保留的韵律。

The sight of a line of battle of twenty thousand Isosceles suddenly facing about, and exchanging the sombre black of their bases for the orange and purple of the two sides including their acute angle; the militia of the Equilateral Triangles tricoloured in red, white, and blue; the mauve, ultramarine, gamboge, and burnt umber of the Square artillerymen rapidly rotating near their vermilion guns; the dashing and flashing of the five-coloured and six-coloured Pentagons and Hexagons careering across the field in their offices of surgeons, geometricians and aides-de-camp—all these may well have been sufficient to render credible the famous story how an illustrious Circle, overcome by the artistic beauty of the forces under his command, threw aside his marshal’s baton and his royal crown, exclaiming that he henceforth exchanged them for the artist’s pencil. How great and glorious the sensuous development of these days must have been is in part indicated by the very language and vocabulary of the period. The commonest utterances of the commonest citizens in the time of the Colour Revolt seem to have been suffused with a richer tinge of word or thought; and to that era we are even now indebted for our finest poetry and for whatever rhythm still remains in the more scientific utterance of those modern days.

§9：论通用颜色表

§ 9: Of the Universal Colour Bill

但与此同时，智力艺术正在迅速衰落。

But meanwhile the intellectual Arts were fast decaying.

视觉辨识术不再需要，也就不再练习了；几何学、静力学、动力学以及其他相关学科的研究很快被认为是多余的，甚至在我们大学里也声名狼藉，无人问津。低劣的感知术很快也在我们的小学遭遇了同样的命运。等腰三角形班级声称标本不再使用也不再需要，并拒绝像犯罪三角形班级那样向教育服务缴纳惯常的贡品，他们凭借着对旧有负担的豁免权，日益壮大，也愈发傲慢自大。这种负担曾经带来双重益处：驯服了他们的野蛮本性，并减少了他们过剩的人数。

The Art of Sight Recognition, being no longer needed, was no longer practised; and the studies of Geometry, Statics, Kinetics, and other kindred subjects, came soon to be considered superfluous, and fell into disrepute and neglect even at our University. The inferior Art of Feeling speedily experienced the same fate at our Elementary Schools. Then the Isosceles classes, asserting that the Specimens were no longer used nor needed, and refusing to pay the customary tribute from the Criminal classes to the service of Education, waxed daily more numerous and more insolent on the strength of their immunity from the old burden which had formerly exercised the twofold wholesome effect of at once taming their brutal nature and thinning their excessive numbers.

士兵和工匠们一年比一年更强烈地宣称——而且越来越真实——他们和那些多边形的最高等级，如今已被提升到与后者平等的地位，并能够通过简单的颜色识别过程，克服一切困难，解决生活中的一切问题，无论是静态的还是动态的。他们不满足于视觉识别自然而然地被忽视，开始大胆地要求法律禁止所有“垄断和贵族化的艺术”，并随之取消对视觉识别、数学和情感研究的所有资助。不久，他们开始坚持认为，既然作为第二天性的色彩已经消除了贵族等级的必要性，法律也应该走同样的道路，从今以后，所有个人和所有阶级都应被视为绝对平等，并享有平等的权利。

Year by year the Soldiers and Artisans began more vehemently to assert—and with increasing truth—that there was no great difference between them and the very highest class of Polygons, now that they were raised to an equality with the latter, and enabled to grapple with all the difficulties and solve all the problems of life, whether Statical or Kinetical, by the simple process of Colour Recognition. Not content with the natural neglect into which Sight Recognition was falling, they began boldly to demand the legal prohibition of all “monopolising and aristocratic Arts” and the consequent abolition of all endowments for the studies of Sight Recognition, Mathematics, and Feeling. Soon, they began to insist that inasmuch as Colour, which was a second Nature, had destroyed the need of aristocratic distinctions, the Law should follow in the same path, and that henceforth all individuals and all classes should be recognized as absolutely equal and entitled to equal rights.

革命领袖们发现上级摇摆不定，便进一步提出了自己的要求，最终要求所有阶层，包括牧师和妇女，都必须接受彩绘，以表达对色彩的敬意。当有人反对牧师和妇女没有侧面时，他们反驳说，自然和权宜之计共同决定了每个人的前半部分（也就是包含眼睛和嘴巴的那一半）应该与后半部分区分开来。因此，他们向平面国所有州的全体特别大会提交了一项法案，提议每个妇女的包含眼睛和嘴巴的那一半应涂成红色，另一半应涂成绿色。牧师也应以同样的方式进行彩绘，红色涂在眼睛和嘴巴中间的半圆上；而另一个半圆，也就是后半圆，则涂成绿色。

Finding the higher Orders wavering and undecided, the leaders of the Revolution advanced still further in their requirements, and at last demanded that all classes alike, the Priests and the Women not excepted, should do homage to Colour by submitting to be painted. When it was objected that Priests and Women had no sides, they retorted that Nature and Expediency concurred in dictating that the front half of every human being (that is to say, the half containing his eye and mouth) should be distinguishable from his hinder half. They therefore brought before a general and extraordinary Assembly of all the States of Flatland a Bill proposing that in every Woman the half containing the eye and mouth should be coloured red, and the other half green. The Priests were to be painted in the same way, red being applied to that semicircle in which the eye and mouth formed the middle point; while the other or hinder semicircle was to be coloured green.

这个建议颇具狡猾之处，事实上，它并非出自某个等腰三角形——因为没有哪个如此堕落的人有足够的棱角去欣赏、更遑论设计出这样的治国之道——而是出自一个不规则的圆形，这个不规则的圆形非但没有在童年时期被毁灭，反而因为愚蠢的放纵而给自己的国家带来了荒凉，也给无数的追随者带来了毁灭。

There was no little cunning in this proposal, which indeed emanated, not from any Isosceles–for no being so degraded would have had angularity enough to appreciate, much less to devise, such a model of state-craft—but from an Irregular Circle who, instead of being destroyed in his childhood, was reserved by a foolish indulgence to bring desolation on his country and destruction on myriads of his followers.

一方面，这项提案旨在将各阶层的女性拉拢到色彩革新派一边。革命者赋予女性与神父相同的两种颜色，从而确保在某些特定位置上，每位女性都像神父一样，并受到相应的尊重和敬重——这样的前景必然会吸引大量女性。

On the one hand the proposition was calculated to bring the Women in all classes over to the side of the Chromatic Innovation. For by assigning to the Women the same two colours as were assigned to the Priests, the Revolutionists thereby ensured that, in certain positions, every Woman would appear like a Priest, and be treated with corresponding respect and deference-a prospect that could not fail to attract the Female Sex in a mass.

但是，我的一些读者可能不会认识到，在新的立法下，牧师和妇女的外表可能相同；如果是这样，一两句话就会使其变得显而易见。

But by some of my Readers the possibility of the identical appearance of Priests and Women, under the new Legislation, may not be recognized; if so, a word or two will make it obvious.

想象一位按照新法典精心装饰的女人：前半身（也就是包含眼睛和嘴巴的那一半）是红色的，后半身是绿色的。从侧面看她。你会看到一条直线，一半是红色，一半是绿色。

Imagine a woman duly decorated, according to the new Code; with the front half (i.e., the half containing eye and mouth) red, and with the hinder half green. Look at her from one side. Obviously you will see a straight line, half red, half green.

现在想象一位牧师，他的嘴巴在 m 处，他的前半圆（AMB）因此被涂成红色，而他的后半圆为绿色；这样直径AB将绿色与红色分开。如果你凝视这位伟人，让你的视线与他的分界直径（AB）处于同一条直线上，你将看到一条直线（CBD），其中一半（CB）为红色，另一半（BD）为绿色。整条线（CD）可能比一个正常大小的女人的线更短，并且向两端更快地渐变；但颜色的同一性会给你一个阶级同一性的直接印象，使你忽略其他细节。记住在颜色革命时期视觉识别的衰退对社会造成的威胁；还要加上女性肯定会很快学会渐变她们的两端以模仿圆圈；那么，我亲爱的读者，您一定已经明白，颜色法案给我们带来了极大的危险，使我们有可能混淆牧师和年轻女子。

Now imagine a Priest, whose mouth is at m, and whose front semicircle (AMB) is consequently coloured red, while his hinder semicircle is green; so that the diameter AB divides the green from the red. If you contemplate the Great Man so as to have your eye in the same straight line as his dividing diameter (AB), what you will see will be a straight line (CBD), of which one half (CB) will be red, and the other (BD) green. The whole line (CD) will be rather shorter perhaps than that of a full-sized Woman, and will shade off more rapidly towards its extremities; but the identity of the colours would give you an immediate impression of identity of Class, making you neglectful of other details. Bear in mind the decay of Sight Recognition which threatened society at the time of the Colour revolt; add too the certainty that Women would speedily learn to shade off their extremities so as to imitate the Circles; it must then be surely obvious to you, my dear Reader, that the Colour Bill placed us under a great danger of confounding a Priest with a young Woman.

不难想象，这种前景对“体弱女性”来说有多么诱人。她们欣喜地期待着随之而来的混乱。在家时，她们可能会听到并非针对她们而是针对她们丈夫和兄弟的政治和教会秘密，甚至可能以教士圈子的名义发布命令；而在户外，红绿相间的醒目组合，不加任何其他颜色，必定会让普通民众犯下无数的错误，而女性则会在路人的尊重中得到“圈子”所失去的一切。至于如果女性轻浮不雅的行为被归咎于“圈子”阶层，会给“圈子”带来什么样的丑闻，以及由此导致的宪法颠覆，女性根本不会考虑这些。即使在“圈子”的家中，女性也都一致支持“通用颜色法案”。

How attractive this prospect must have been to the Frail Sex may readily be imagined. They anticipated with delight the confusion that would ensue. At home they might hear political and ecclesiastical secrets intended not for them but for their husbands and brothers, and might even issue commands in the name of a priestly Circle; out of doors the striking combination of red and green, without addition of any other colours, would be sure to lead the common people into endless mistakes, and the Women would gain whatever the Circles lost, in the deference of the passers by. As for the scandal that would befall the Circular Class if the frivolous and unseemly conduct of the Women were imputed to them, and as to the consequent subversion of the Constitution, the Female Sex could not be expected to give a thought to these considerations. Even in the households of the Circles, the Women were all in favour of the Universal Colour Bill.

该法案的第二个目标是逐渐瓦解圈子本身的道德败坏。在普遍的智力衰退时期，他们仍然保持着原始的清晰和强大的理解力。从幼年起，在圈子里的家庭中，贵族们就熟悉了完全没有色彩的环境，唯有他们保留了神圣的视觉识别术，并享有这种令人钦佩的智力训练所带来的所有优势。因此，直到《通用颜色法案》颁布之日，圈子们不仅保持了自身的地位，甚至通过摒弃流行时尚，进一步领先于其他阶层。

The second object aimed at by the Bill was the gradual demoralization of the Circles themselves. In the general intellectual decay they still preserved their pristine clearness and strength of understanding. From their earliest childhood, familiarized in their Circular households with the total absence of Colour, the Nobles alone preserved the Sacred Art of Sight Recognition, with all the advantages that result from that admirable training of the intellect. Hence, up to the date of the introduction of the Universal Colour Bill, the Circles had not only held their own, but even increased their lead of other classes by abstinence from the popular fashion.

因此，我之前描述的那个狡猾的不规则者，也就是这项恶魔法案的真正作者，决心一举降低教会的地位，迫使他们屈服于色彩的污染，同时摧毁他们在家中学习视觉识别术的机会，剥夺他们纯洁无色的家园，从而削弱他们的智力。一旦受到色彩污染，每一个父母和每一个孩子都会互相败坏。只有在辨别父亲和母亲时，圆形婴儿才会遇到需要运用其理解力的问题——而这些问题往往容易被母亲的欺骗所腐蚀，最终动摇孩子对所有逻辑结论的信念。就这样，祭司阶层的智识光辉将逐渐消退，彻底摧毁所有贵族立法机构，颠覆我们的特权阶级的道路也将随之打开。

Now therefore the artful Irregular whom I described above as the real author of this diabolical Bill, determined at one blow to lower the status of the Hierarchy by forcing them to submit to the pollution of Colour, and at the same time to destroy their domestic opportunities of training in the Art of Sight Recognition, so as to enfeeble their intellects by depriving them of their pure and colourless homes. Once subjected to the chromatic taint, every parental and every childish Circle would demoralize each other. Only in discerning between the Father and the Mother would the Circular infant find problems for the exercise of its understanding—problems too often likely to be corrupted by maternal impostures with the result of shaking the child’s faith in all logical conclusions. Thus by degrees the intellectual lustre of the Priestly Order would wane, and the road would then lie open for a total destruction of all Aristocratic Legislature and for the subversion of our Privileged Classes.

§10：论镇压彩色叛乱

§ 10: Of the Suppression of the Chromatic Sedition

争取普遍彩色法案的运动持续了三年；直到那段时期的最后一刻，无政府主义似乎注定要胜利。

The agitation for the Universal Colour Bill continued for three years; and up to the last moment of that period it seemed as though Anarchy were destined to triumph.

一整支多边形阵营，原本只是以私兵身份参战，却被实力更胜一筹的等腰三角形阵营彻底歼灭——与此同时，正方形阵营和五边形阵营保持中立。更糟糕的是，一些最有能力的圆形阵营竟然沦为夫妻之间争吵的牺牲品。许多贵族家庭的妻子们被政治仇恨激怒，不断向领主祈祷，要求他们放弃反对颜色法案的立场，令领主厌烦不已；而有些妻子们发现恳求无果，便转而屠杀无辜的子女和丈夫，自己也葬身于这场屠杀之中。据记载，在那场三年一度的骚乱中，至少有二十三个圆形阵营死于家庭不和。

A whole army of Polygons, who turned out to fight as private soldiers, was utterly annihilated by a superior force of Isosceles Triangles—the Squares and Pentagons meanwhile remaining neutral. Worse than all, some of the ablest Circles fell a prey to conjugal fury. Infuriated by political animosity, the wives in many a noble household wearied their lords with prayers to give up their opposition to the Colour Bill; and some, finding their entreaties fruitless, fell on and slaughtered their innocent children and husbands, perishing themselves in the act of carnage. It is recorded that during that triennial agitation no less than twenty-three Circles perished in domestic discord.

危险确实巨大。僧侣们似乎别无选择，要么屈服，要么被消灭；突然间，事态的进程被一件引人注目的事件彻底改变。政治家们不应该忽视这些事件，他们常常应该预见这些事件，有时甚至应该主动发起这些事件，因为他们用荒谬而不相称的力量来诉诸民众的同情。

Great indeed was the peril. It seemed as though the Priests had no choice between submission and extermination; when suddenly the course of events was completely changed by one of those picturesque incidents which Statesmen ought never to neglect, often to anticipate, and sometimes perhaps to originate, because of the absurdly disproportionate power with which they appeal to the sympathies of the populace.

有一次，一个低等腰三角形，脑子只有四度，甚至几度都没有——他无意中沾染了某个商人的颜料，而那个商人的店铺正是他抢劫的。他给自己涂上了十二边形的十二种颜色，或者说，是让人给自己涂上了（因为传说各不相同）十二边形的颜色。他走进市场，用假嗓子搭讪一位少女，她是一位多边形贵族的孤女，他过去曾徒劳地追求过她的爱情；他用一系列的欺骗手段——一方面，借助于一连串难以言喻的幸运事件，另一方面，借助于一种近乎……新娘亲属的愚蠢程度令人难以置信，且疏忽了日常防范措施——他成功地完成了这场婚事。不幸的女孩发现自己遭受了欺骗后，选择了自杀。

It happened that an Isosceles of a low type, with a brain little if at all above four degrees—accidentally dabbling in the colours of some Tradesman whose shop he had plundered—painted himself, or caused himself to be painted (for the story varies) with the twelve colours of a Dodecagon. Going into the Market Place he accosted in a feigned voice a maiden, the orphan daughter of a noble Polygon, whose affection in former days he had sought in vain; and by a series of deceptions—aided, on the one side, by a string of lucky accidents too long to relate, and, on the other, by an almost inconceivable fatuity and neglect of ordinary precautions on the part of the relations of the bride—he succeeded in consummating the marriage. The unhappy girl committed suicide on discovering the fraud to which she had been subjected.

当这场灾难的消息传遍各州时，妇女们的内心都激动不已。对这位悲惨受害者的同情，以及对她们自己、姐妹和女儿遭受类似欺骗的预感，使她们对《颜色法案》有了全新的认识。不少人公开宣称自己已经转向敌对；其余人只需稍加刺激，也会做出类似的表态。抓住这个有利时机，各区迅速召开了一次各州特别议会；除了惯常的囚犯守卫外，她们还争取到了大量反动妇女的参与。

When the news of this catastrophe spread from State to State the minds of the Women were violently agitated. Sympathy with the miserable victim and anticipations of similar deceptions for themselves, their sisters, and their daughters, made them now regard the Colour Bill in an entirely new aspect. Not a few openly avowed themselves converted to antagonism; the rest needed only a slight stimulus to make a similar avowal. Seizing this favourable opportunity, the Circles hastily convened an extraordinary Assembly of the States; and besides the usual guard of Convicts, they secured the attendance of a large number of reactionary Women.

在空前的人群中，当时的首席圈子——名叫潘托基勒斯——站了起来，却发现十二万等腰三角形的人们发出嘘声和喝彩。但他宣布，从今以后，圈子们将采取让步政策；他们将顺从多数人的意愿，接受颜色法案，以此来确保大家的安静。喧闹声立刻转化为掌声，他邀请叛乱领袖色论者到大厅中央，以他的追随者的名义接受教会的臣服。随后，他发表了一场雄辩的演讲，这场演讲几乎持续了一天，任何总结都无法公正地评价其内容。

Amidst an unprecedented concourse, the Chief Circle of those days—by name Pantocyclus—arose to find himself hissed and hooted by a hundred and twenty thousand Isosceles. But he secured silence by declaring that henceforth the Circles would enter on a policy of Concession; yielding to the wishes of the majority, they would accept the Colour Bill. The uproar being at once converted to applause, he invited Chromatistes, the leader of the Sedition, into the centre of the hall, to receive in the name of his followers the submission of the Hierarchy. Then followed a speech, a masterpiece of rhetoric, which occupied nearly a day in the delivery, and to which no summary can do justice.

他以一副严肃公正的姿态宣布，既然他们最终决定进行改革或创新，最好对整个议题的方方面面，包括其优缺点，进行最后一次审视。他逐渐提到了法案对商人、专业人士和绅士们的危害，并提醒他们，尽管存在诸多缺陷，但如果法案获得多数票通过，他愿意接受，以此平息了等腰三角形阵营日益高涨的议论。但显然，除了等腰三角形阵营外，所有人都被他的话所触动，对该法案要么持中立态度，要么持反对态度。

With a grave appearance of impartiality he declared that, as they were now finally committing themselves to Reform or Innovation, it was desirable that they should take one last view of the perimeter of the whole subject, its defects as well as its advantages. Gradually introducing the mention of the dangers to the Tradesmen, the Professional Classes and the Gentlemen, he silenced the rising murmurs of the Isosceles by reminding them that, in spite of all these defects, he was willing to accept the Bill if it was approved by the majority. But it was manifest that all, except the Isosceles, were moved by his words and were either neutral or averse to the Bill.

现在他转向工人，坚称他们的利益不容忽视，如果他们打算接受颜色法案，至少应该充分考虑其后果。他说，他们中的许多人即将被纳入“规则三角形”阶层；其他人则期待着自己的孩子获得他们自己无法企及的荣誉。现在，这一光荣的抱负必须被牺牲。随着颜色法案的普遍采用，所有的区别都将消失；规则性将与非规则性混淆；发展将让位于倒退；几代人之后，工人将沦为军人，甚至是囚犯阶层；政治权力将掌握在大多数人手中，也就是说，掌握在那些已经……他们的人数比工人还多，而且当自然的补偿法则被违反时，他们的数量很快就会超过所有其他阶层的总和。

Turning now to the Workmen he asserted that their interests must not be neglected, and that, if they intended to accept the Colour Bill, they ought at least to do so with a full view of the consequences. Many of them, he said, were on the point of being admitted to the class of the Regular Triangles; others anticipated for their children a distinction they could not hope for themselves. That honourable ambition would now have to be sacrificed. With the universal adoption of Colour, all distinctions would cease; Regularity would be confused with Irregularity; development would give place to retrogression; the Workman would in a few generations be degraded to the level of the Military, or even the Convict Class; political power would be in the hands of the greatest number, that is to say the Criminal Classes, who were already more numerous than the Workmen, and would soon out-number all the other Classes put together when the usual Compensative Laws of Nature were violated.

工匠们阵阵低声表示赞同，色教徒们惊慌失措，试图上前发言。但他发现自己被卫兵包围，被迫保持沉默。这时，首席圆桌用几句激昂的话语向妇女们发出了最后的呼吁，他大声疾呼，如果《颜色法案》获得通过，从此以后，任何婚姻都将不稳固，任何女性的荣誉都将得不到保障；欺诈、欺骗和虚伪将充斥家家户户；家庭幸福将与宪法同归于尽，迅速走向毁灭。“死神来了，”他喊道，“死神来了。”

A subdued murmur of assent ran through the ranks of the Artisans, and Chromatistes, in alarm, attempted to step forward and address them. But he found himself encompassed with guards and forced to remain silent while the Chief Circle in a few impassioned words made a final appeal to the Women, exclaiming that, if the Colour Bill passed, no marriage would henceforth be safe, no woman’s honour secure; fraud, deception, hypocrisy would pervade every household; domestic bliss would share the fate of the Constitution and pass to speedy perdition. “Sooner than this,” he cried, “Come death.”

这句话，如同事先商定好的行动信号，等腰囚犯们猛扑向可怜的色阶囚犯，将他们牢牢地钉在地上；普通囚犯们也纷纷散开队伍，为一队妇女让路。妇女们在圆圈囚犯的指挥下，从最前面退到最前面，隐蔽而精准地攻击着昏迷不醒的士兵；工匠们也效仿他们的上级，散开了队伍。与此同时，囚犯们排成坚不可摧的方阵，把守着每个入口。

At these words, which were the preconcerted signal for action, the Isosceles Convicts fell on and transfixed the wretched Chromatistes; the Regular Classes, opening their ranks, made way for a band of Women who, under direction of the Circles, moved, back foremost, invisibly and unerringly upon the unconscious Soldiers; the Artisans, imitating the example of their betters, also opened their ranks. Meantime bands of Convicts occupied every entrance with an impenetrable phalanx.

战斗，或者更确切地说是屠杀，持续时间很短。在圆圈女战士的巧妙指挥下，几乎每个女战士的冲锋都致命，许多女战士毫发无损地拔出了毒刺，准备再次屠杀。但无需第二次打击；等腰三角形的乌合之众自己完成了剩下的任务。他们措手不及，群龙无首，正面遭到看不见的敌人袭击，后方的囚犯又切断了出口，他们立刻——按照他们的方式——失去了理智，高喊“叛徒”。这注定了他们的命运。现在，每个等腰三角形都看到并感觉到彼此都是敌人。半小时内，这庞大的人群中无一幸存；七万名囚犯被彼此的角杀死，残骸证明了秩序的胜利。

The battle, or rather carnage, was of short duration. Under the skilful generalship of the Circles almost every Woman’s charge was fatal, and very many extracted their sting uninjured, ready for a second slaughter. But no second blow was needed; the rabble of the Isosceles did the rest of the business for themselves. Surprised, leaderless, attacked in front by invisible foes, and finding egress cut off by the Convicts behind them, they at once—after their manner—lost all presence of mind, and raised the cry of “treachery.” This sealed their fate. Every Isosceles now saw and felt a foe in every other. In half an hour not one of that vast multitude was living; and the fragments of seven score thousand of the Criminal Class slain by one another’s angles attested the triumph of Order.

圆圈族毫不迟疑地将胜利推向极致。他们放过了工人，却伤亡惨重。等边形民兵立即被召集；每一个被合理怀疑有不规则之处的三角形，都未经社会委员会的精确测量就被军事法庭摧毁。军人和工匠阶层的住宅在长达一年多的巡查中被逐一检查；在此期间，每个城镇、村庄和小村庄都被系统地清除了下层阶级的过剩人口，这些过剩人口是由于他们忽视向学校和大学缴纳罪犯贡金，以及违反了平面国宪法的其他自然法而造成的。就这样，阶级之间的平衡再次得以恢复。

The Circles delayed not to push their victory to the uttermost. The Working Men they spared but decimated. The Militia of the Equilaterals was at once called out; and every Triangle suspected of Irregularity on reasonable grounds, was destroyed by Court Martial, without the formality of exact measurement by the Social Board. The homes of the Military and Artisan classes were inspected in a course of visitations extending through upwards of a year; and during that period every town, village, and hamlet was systematically purged of that excess of the lower orders which had been brought about by the neglect to pay the Tribute of Criminals to the Schools and University, and by the violation of the other natural Laws of the Constitution of Flatland. Thus the balance of classes was again restored.

毋庸置疑，从此以后，颜色的使用被废除，拥有颜色也被禁止。甚至任何表示颜色的词语，除了圆圈之外，都不能被提及。或由合格的科学教师讲授，都会受到严厉的惩罚。只有在我们大学一些最高级、最深奥的课程中——我自己从未有幸旁听过——人们才知道，为了阐明一些更深层次的数学问题，少量使用颜色仍然是允许的。但对此，我只能说是道听途说。

Needless to say that henceforth the use of Colour was abolished, and its possession prohibited. Even the utterance of any word denoting Colour, except by the Circles or by qualified scientific teachers, was punished by a severe penalty. Only at our University in some of the very highest and most esoteric classes—which I myself have never been privileged to attend—it is understood that the sparing use of Colour is still sanctioned for the purpose of illustrating some of the deeper problems of mathematics. But of this I can only speak from hearsay.

在平面国的其他地方，彩色颜料如今已不复存在。只有一位在世之人掌握着制作彩色颜料的技艺，也就是当时的圆顶长官；他临终前，也只将这门技艺传授给他的继承人。只有一家工厂生产彩色颜料；为了防止秘密泄露，工厂每年都会把工人换掉，然后再引进新的工人。即使是现在，我们的贵族阶层回想起那些遥远的、为争取普遍彩色法案而奔走呼号的日子，也依然心怀恐惧。

Elsewhere in Flatland, Colour is now non-existent. The art of making it is known to only one living person, the Chief Circle for the time being; and by him it is handed down on his death-bed to none but his Successor. One manufactory alone produces it; and, lest the secret should be betrayed, the Workmen are annually consumed, and fresh ones introduced. So great is the terror with which even now our Aristocracy looks back to the far-distant days of the agitation for the Universal Colour Bill.

§11：关于我们的司铎

§ 11: Concerning our Priests

现在是时候结束这些关于平面国事物的简短散漫的笔记，转入本书的核心内容——我探索太空奥秘的初体验。这才是我的主题；之前的一切只是序言。

It is high time that I should pass from these brief and discursive notes about things in Flatland to the central event of this book, my initiation into the mysteries of Space. That is my subject; all that has gone before is merely preface.

因此，我必须省略许多内容，但我认为，对这些内容的解释不会让读者不感兴趣：例如，我们虽然没有双脚，却仍然能够推动和阻止自己前进；我们虽然没有双手，也不能像你们那样打地基，也不能利用地球的侧压力，却仍然能够固定木头、石头或砖块结构；雨水如何在我们各个区域之间的间隙中产生，以至于北部地区不会阻挡降落在南部地区的水分；我们的山丘和矿山、树木和蔬菜、季节和收成的性质；适合线性碑文的字母表；适合线性侧面的眼睛；这些以及其他数百种有关我们物质存在的细节，我都必须略过；我现在之所以不提它们，只是为了向读者表明，省略它们并非由于作者的健忘，而是出于对读者时间的考虑。

For this reason I must omit many matters of which the explanation would not, I flatter myself, be without interest for my Readers: as for example, our method of propelling and stopping ourselves, although destitute of feet; the means by which we give fixity to structures of wood, stone, or brick, although of course we have no hands, nor can we lay foundations as you can, nor avail ourselves of the lateral pressure of the earth; the manner in which the rain originates in the intervals between our various zones, so that the northern regions do not intercept the moisture falling on the southern; the nature of our hills and mines, our trees and vegetables, our seasons and harvests; our Alphabet, suited to our linear tablets; our eyes adapted to our linear sides; these and a hundred other details of our physical existence I must pass over; nor do I mention them now except to indicate to my readers that their omission proceeds, not from forgetfulness on the part of the Author, but from his regard for the time of the Reader.

然而，在我继续讨论我的合法主题之前，读者无疑会期望我对平面国宪法的支柱和主心骨、我们行为的控制者和我们命运的塑造者、普遍敬意和几乎崇拜的对象发表最后几句评论：我需要说我指的是我们的圈子或牧师吗？

Yet before I proceed to my legitimate subject some few final remarks will no doubt be expected by my Readers upon those pillars and mainstays of the Constitution of Flatland, the controllers of our conduct and shapers of our destiny, the objects of universal homage and almost of adoration: need I say that I mean our Circles or Priests?

当我称他们为神父时，请不要误以为我的意思仅仅局限于这个词在你们那里的含义。在我们这里，我们的神父是所有商业、艺术和科学的管理者；是贸易、商业、军事、建筑、工程的主管，教育、政治才能、立法、道德、神学；他们自己什么都不做，但他们是别人所做的一切值得做的事情的原因。

When I call them Priests, let me not be understood as meaning no more than the term denotes with you. With us, our Priests are Administrators of all Business, Art, and Science; Directors of Trade, Commerce, Generalship, Architecture, Engineering, Education, Statesmanship, Legislature, Morality, Theology; doing nothing themselves, they are the Causes of everything, worth doing, that is done by others.

虽然通常情况下，所有被称为圆的东西都被认为是圆，但在受过良好教育的阶层中，人们知道没有一个圆是真正的圆，而是一个由大量小边组成的多边形。随着边数的增加，多边形逐渐接近圆；而当边数非常大时，比如三四百条边，即使是最灵敏的触觉也很难感受到任何多边形的角。我更确切地说，这很难：因为正如我上面所指出的，在上流社会中，通过感觉来识别是未知的，而触摸一个圆会被认为是一种极其大胆的侮辱。这种在上流社会中回避感觉的习惯，使得圆更容易保持神秘的面纱，从幼年起，它就习惯于将周长或圆周的确切性质隐藏在其中。假设三英尺是平均周长，那么，一个有三百条边的多边形，每条边的长度不会超过百分之一英尺，或者略大于十分之一英寸；而一个有六七百条边的多边形，每条边的长度略大于太空国针头的直径。出于礼貌，我们总是假设主圆目前有1万条边。

Although popularly everyone called a Circle is deemed a Circle, yet among the better educated Classes it is known that no Circle is really a Circle, but only a Polygon with a very large number of very small sides. As the number of the sides increases, a Polygon approximates to a Circle; and, when the number is very great indeed, say for example three or four hundred, it is extremely difficult for the most delicate touch to feel any polygonal angles. Let me say rather, it would be difficult: for, as I have shown above, Recognition by Feeling is unknown among the highest society, and to feel a Circle would be considered a most audacious insult. This habit of abstention from Feeling in the best society enables a Circle the more easily to sustain the veil of mystery in which, from his earliest years, he is wont to enwrap the exact nature of his Perimeter or Circumference. Three feet being the average Perimeter it follows that, in a Polygon of three hundred sides, each side will be no more than the hundredth part of a foot in length, or little more than the tenth part of an inch; and in a Polygon of six or seven hundred sides the sides are little larger than the diameter of a Spaceland pin-head. It is always assumed, by courtesy, that the Chief Circle for the time being has ten thousand sides.

圆形后代在社会阶层中的晋升不受自然法则的限制，不像低等的规则阶层那样，自然法则规定每代边数只能增加一条。如果是这样，圆形的边数就仅仅是血统和算术的问题了，等边三角形的第四百九十七个后代必然会是一个有五百条边的多边形。但事实并非如此。自然法则规定了两条影响圆形繁衍的相互对立的法则：第一，随着种族在发展阶梯上的攀升，发展速度也会加快；第二，以同样的比例，种族的生育能力会下降。因此，在一个四五百条边的多边形的家中，很难找到儿子；从未见过超过一个的。另一方面，一个五百条边的多边形的儿子，据说有五百五十条，甚至六百条边。

The ascent of the posterity of the Circles in the social scale is not restricted, as it is among the lower Regular classes, by the Law of Nature which limits the increase of sides to one in each generation. If it were so, the number of sides in a Circle would be a mere question of pedigree and arithmetic, and the four hundred and ninety-seventh descendant of an Equilateral Triangle would necessarily be a Polygon with five hundred sides. But this is not the case. Nature’s Law prescribes two antagonistic decrees affecting Circular propagation; first, that as the race climbs higher in the scale of development, so development shall proceed at an accelerated pace; second, that in the same proportion, the race shall become less fertile. Consequently in the home of a Polygon of four or five hundred sides it is rare to find a son; more than one is never seen. On the other hand the son of a five-hundred-sided Polygon has been known to possess five hundred and fifty, or even six hundred sides.

艺术也介入，助力更高阶的进化进程。我们的医生发现，可以将高级多边形婴儿细小而柔嫩的侧面折断，然后将其整个框架重新接回，其精确度之高，有时——并非总是如此，因为这个过程伴随着巨大的风险——一个拥有两三百条边的多边形，有时甚至能够跨越两三百代，仿佛一下子就将其祖先的数量和血统的贵族身份翻了一番。

Art also steps in to help the process of higher Evolution. Our physicians have discovered that the small and tender sides of an infant Polygon of the higher class can be fractured, and his whole frame re-set, with such exactness that a Polygon of two or three hundred sides sometimes—by no means always, for the process is attended with serious risk—but sometimes overleaps two or three hundred generations, and as it were doubles at a stroke, the number of his progenitors and the nobility of his descent.

许多有前途的孩子就这样被牺牲了，几乎只有十分之一的孩子能够存活下来。然而，在那些处于圆形阶级边缘的多边形人中，父母的野心是如此强烈，以至于很少能找到一个具有这一社会地位的贵族，在自己的第一个儿子满月之前就忽略了把他送进圆形新治疗中心。

Many a promising child is sacrificed in this way. Scarcely one out of ten survives. Yet so strong is the parental ambition among those Polygons who are, as it were, on the fringe of the Circular class, that it is very rare to find a Nobleman, of that position in society, who has neglected to place his first-born son in the Circular Neo-Therapeutic Gymnasium before he has attained the age of a month.
